WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:05.030
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress, in Washington D.C.

00:00:17.060 --> 00:00:19.150
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Hi, Good
evening, ladies and gentlemen.

00:00:19.150 --> 00:00:21.440
Great to have you
with us tonight.

00:00:21.440 --> 00:00:23.750
Welcome to the Library
of Congress.

00:00:23.750 --> 00:00:31.050
Welcome to the kickoff of La voz
latina, which is a series long

00:00:31.050 --> 00:00:35.060
in the making, I guess
it was about a year ago,

00:00:35.060 --> 00:00:40.000
Alicia and Giorda, we were
talking with the Kennedy Center

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:43.210
and managed this
wonderful collaboration

00:00:43.210 --> 00:00:46.610
between the Library of
Congress and the Kennedy Center.

00:00:46.610 --> 00:00:49.520
There Will be two more
programs tomorrow night.

00:00:49.520 --> 00:00:52.740
I Will -- Sorry,
Saturday, all day long,

00:00:52.740 --> 00:00:55.670
and I encourage you to go.

00:00:55.670 --> 00:00:59.720
The first program at
eleven o'clock will be

00:00:59.720 --> 00:01:04.600
with Natasha Trethewey,
the U.S. poet laureate,

00:01:04.600 --> 00:01:09.680
and Jorge Ignacio Cortiñas,
who is a wonderful playwright,

00:01:09.680 --> 00:01:13.830
Cuban playwright, and they
will present a program,

00:01:13.830 --> 00:01:18.290
a really wonderful program on
the relationship and friendship

00:01:18.290 --> 00:01:24.010
between two great poets,
Nicolás Guillén, of Cuba,

00:01:24.010 --> 00:01:26.770
and Langston Hughes,
of the United States,

00:01:26.770 --> 00:01:29.960
who were great friends
and wonderful poets,

00:01:29.960 --> 00:01:32.090
and translated one another.

00:01:32.090 --> 00:01:35.660
The other program
is at two o'clock,

00:01:35.660 --> 00:01:42.300
and that would be a cavalcade
of great Latin American

00:01:42.300 --> 00:01:47.320
and Latino American writers,
and you can see in your program

00:01:47.320 --> 00:01:50.870
who they are, is a
magnificent lineup [inaudible]

00:01:50.870 --> 00:01:54.590
which I encourage you to come
on Saturday, eleven o'clock

00:01:54.590 --> 00:01:58.960
and two o'clock, and between
those programs, Rolando Estévez,

00:01:58.960 --> 00:02:03.550
who you see here
tonight, the great,

00:02:03.550 --> 00:02:08.010
wonderful master bookmaker
that we are very lucky to have

00:02:08.010 --> 00:02:11.710
in the Library of Congress
tonight will be presenting more

00:02:11.710 --> 00:02:16.230
of his books that are on their
way, right now, from Habana,

00:02:16.230 --> 00:02:20.170
large scale material that
he has brought as well.

00:02:20.170 --> 00:02:24.620
So, the display, if you've seen
it, is absolutely marvelous,

00:02:24.620 --> 00:02:30.580
breathtaking work that he
has produced over the years,

00:02:30.580 --> 00:02:33.280
and the display at the
Kennedy Center will be an

00:02:33.280 --> 00:02:34.650
additional bonus.

00:02:34.650 --> 00:02:39.620
So, I would encourage
you to go to that.

00:02:40.730 --> 00:02:47.230
We are very, very indebted
to the extraordinary director

00:02:47.230 --> 00:02:53.160
of the international programing
at the Kennedy Center,

00:02:53.160 --> 00:02:57.850
Alicia Adams, and ger fantastic
dynamo colleague Giorda Almada.

00:02:57.850 --> 00:03:01.000
We are very proud of
this collaboration

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:03.190
between the Library
and the Kennedy Center.

00:03:03.190 --> 00:03:08.660
I think it may be
the - unprecedented,

00:03:08.660 --> 00:03:12.870
a first collaboration of this
sort of scholarly material,

00:03:12.870 --> 00:03:17.040
we think so, and so we hope
that it will be the first

00:03:17.040 --> 00:03:20.910
of many other collaborations
in the future.

00:03:20.910 --> 00:03:25.960
So, I want to bring on Alicia
to say a few words to you.

00:03:25.960 --> 00:03:28.620
Alicia Adams, as I
say, is the director

00:03:28.620 --> 00:03:31.070
of the International Program
in the Kennedy Center.

00:03:31.070 --> 00:03:33.270
It is through her

00:03:33.270 --> 00:03:36.420
that Washington audiences
have been treated to authors

00:03:36.420 --> 00:03:41.050
from really all around
the world,

00:03:41.050 --> 00:03:45.450
from China to Scandinavia,
to Africa, to all the Spanish

00:03:45.450 --> 00:03:49.160
and Portuguese-speaking
nations, the Middle East,

00:03:49.160 --> 00:03:54.250
India and many other fascinating
places whose art we might not

00:03:54.250 --> 00:03:57.790
know but for her efforts
and those of her colleagues,

00:03:57.790 --> 00:04:01.770
like Giorda, and the very
efficient Ginger Rogers,

00:04:01.770 --> 00:04:03.510
thank you, Ginger.

00:04:03.510 --> 00:04:07.500
If you were to keep track
of Alicia's productions,

00:04:07.500 --> 00:04:11.690
you could virtually tour
the world and see artists

00:04:11.690 --> 00:04:15.170
and art forms that you
hadn't imagined existed,

00:04:15.170 --> 00:04:18.030
from the comfort of your
seat at the Kennedy Center.

00:04:18.030 --> 00:04:19.530
So I'd like to ask
Alicia to come up

00:04:19.530 --> 00:04:21.970
and say a few words,
if you would.

00:04:23.270 --> 00:04:25.070
Alicia Adams.

00:04:25.070 --> 00:04:30.610
[ Aplausos ]

00:04:30.610 --> 00:04:31.910
&gt;&gt; Alicia Adams: Thank
you so much, Marie,

00:04:31.910 --> 00:04:33.310
that's quite an introduction.

00:04:33.310 --> 00:04:36.790
I don't know if I can live up
to that right now, but [risa].

00:04:36.790 --> 00:04:39.630
I'd like to thank you
all for coming tonight

00:04:39.630 --> 00:04:41.550
to tonight's literary
collaboration

00:04:41.550 --> 00:04:43.960
between the Kennedy
Center and the Library

00:04:43.960 --> 00:04:46.430
of Congress, La voz latina.

00:04:46.430 --> 00:04:48.810
I do carry the international
festivals

00:04:48.810 --> 00:04:52.200
with the Kennedy Center and we
just finished a major festival

00:04:52.200 --> 00:04:56.290
on Cuba called Artes de Cuba:
From the Island to the World.

00:04:56.290 --> 00:04:58.600
Literature has always
been important to me,

00:04:58.600 --> 00:05:01.040
for all of the festivals,
and I'm so pleased

00:05:01.040 --> 00:05:06.300
that tonight we begin an
addition to the Cuba festival

00:05:06.300 --> 00:05:09.090
with writers from Cuba, but also

00:05:09.090 --> 00:05:11.790
that we will have
other latino voices.

00:05:11.790 --> 00:05:14.610
So From the Island to
the World comes alive

00:05:14.610 --> 00:05:18.120
for me and for us tonight.

00:05:18.120 --> 00:05:21.580
I'm thrilled that we are looking
at another aspect of the book,

00:05:21.580 --> 00:05:25.950
the art of the book, with
the work of Rolando Estévez.

00:05:25.950 --> 00:05:28.630
These handmade books
are so beautiful

00:05:28.630 --> 00:05:31.800
and if you haven't had a
look at the books that are

00:05:31.800 --> 00:05:35.520
in the other room,
please, do so.

00:05:35.520 --> 00:05:39.690
The only time I've ever seen
such beautiful handmade books is

00:05:39.690 --> 00:05:43.650
at the Booker Prize in London
that I go to every year,

00:05:43.650 --> 00:05:47.910
every other year, and they
always present to the five --

00:05:47.910 --> 00:05:53.650
the five finalists a
handmade book by an artist.

00:05:53.650 --> 00:05:55.230
So, they are always
so beautiful.

00:05:55.230 --> 00:06:00.240
I'd just never seen so many
beautiful books together.

00:06:00.240 --> 00:06:02.030
There are only five there.

00:06:02.030 --> 00:06:05.710
But I think that these
books, these book covers,

00:06:05.710 --> 00:06:10.520
the books themselves, give us
another entry into the story

00:06:10.520 --> 00:06:13.510
that will be told inside.

00:06:13.510 --> 00:06:16.080
It invites us in a
very different way

00:06:16.080 --> 00:06:19.630
than a book that's
printed by the printer.

00:06:19.630 --> 00:06:23.090
And that's something that
I find very exciting.

00:06:23.090 --> 00:06:24.390
It's another aspect of the art

00:06:24.390 --> 00:06:27.770
that I think we should
pay attention to.

00:06:27.770 --> 00:06:31.060
I'm so pleased that Ruth
Behar and Marie Arana thought

00:06:31.060 --> 00:06:34.690
to have this as part
of this collaboration

00:06:34.690 --> 00:06:37.160
and this literary event tonight.

00:06:37.160 --> 00:06:41.880
I have to say that
this is the first time

00:06:41.880 --> 00:06:44.500
that we've collaborated with
the Library of Congress,

00:06:44.500 --> 00:06:48.160
the Kennedy Center, but this
is probably the fiftieth time

00:06:48.160 --> 00:06:50.380
that I've collaborated
with Marie.

00:06:50.380 --> 00:06:53.730
I have followed her wherever
she went, I met her probably

00:06:53.730 --> 00:06:57.990
over 20 years ago, and she
is a writer extraordinaire

00:06:57.990 --> 00:07:00.230
when she was the book
editor of The Post,

00:07:00.230 --> 00:07:04.090
she did a fantastic job, and
here at the Library of Congress,

00:07:04.090 --> 00:07:07.130
with the National Book
Fair it's extraordinary

00:07:07.130 --> 00:07:10.200
that we see thousands and
thousands of people there.

00:07:10.200 --> 00:07:14.850
No matter what the title of the
festival is, if I can find a way

00:07:14.850 --> 00:07:18.900
to involve Marie in it, I
will, if only for advice,

00:07:18.900 --> 00:07:22.420
but many of them have
included Latino artists

00:07:22.420 --> 00:07:25.140
or African artists or
I've involved her sister,

00:07:25.140 --> 00:07:32.090
I believe so, it's been a great
partnership and I love her,

00:07:32.090 --> 00:07:35.820
she is a dear friend, I'm
so glad that she's been able

00:07:35.820 --> 00:07:39.820
to put together this series
over the next few days.

00:07:39.820 --> 00:07:42.510
So thank you, thank
you again for coming.

00:07:42.510 --> 00:07:51.510
[ Aplausos ]

00:07:51.510 --> 00:07:52.810
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Oh, my goodness,

00:07:52.810 --> 00:07:55.510
I am glowing, thank
you very much.

00:07:55.510 --> 00:07:58.070
Such a special friend,
absolutely.

00:07:58.070 --> 00:08:01.020
Well, we have a very
exciting program for you

00:08:01.020 --> 00:08:02.320
in store this evening.

00:08:02.320 --> 00:08:06.220
The participants, as you can
see, have come from far and near

00:08:06.220 --> 00:08:09.570
to tell you about a singular,
really truly singular art form

00:08:09.570 --> 00:08:15.080
that fuses a love of
books with a love for art.

00:08:15.080 --> 00:08:18.110
We are very, very
honored, deeply honored,

00:08:18.110 --> 00:08:25.340
profoundly honored to present
Rolando Estévez, a poet, writer,

00:08:25.340 --> 00:08:30.060
producer, and master bookmaker
whose handy work the Library

00:08:30.060 --> 00:08:31.780
of Congress has been collecting

00:08:31.780 --> 00:08:35.850
in its Rare Book Division
for many, many years.

00:08:35.850 --> 00:08:38.100
Here to tell you
about that collection,

00:08:38.100 --> 00:08:41.290
the Vigia Collection is my
colleague, Catalina Gómez,

00:08:41.290 --> 00:08:43.890
who is sitting on
the extreme far end,

00:08:43.890 --> 00:08:47.470
without whom this program
and the two other programs

00:08:47.470 --> 00:08:48.770
that will take place

00:08:48.770 --> 00:08:52.030
at the Kennedy Center would
not have been possible.

00:08:52.030 --> 00:08:54.010
Thank you, Catalina.

00:08:54.010 --> 00:08:56.760
Ruth will tell you more
about Rolando and Catalina,

00:08:56.760 --> 00:09:00.490
but let me tell you a
little bit about Ruth.

00:09:00.490 --> 00:09:02.090
Ruth, our moderator sitting

00:09:02.090 --> 00:09:06.110
in the middle this evening is
a Cuban-American anthropologist

00:09:06.110 --> 00:09:09.580
and writer, a professor
of cultural anthropology

00:09:09.580 --> 00:09:13.190
at the University of Michigan,
her work straddles the worlds

00:09:13.190 --> 00:09:17.120
of the academy and popular
books, she's written poetry,

00:09:17.120 --> 00:09:21.510
memoirs, literary fiction,
books for children, she was born

00:09:21.510 --> 00:09:24.190
in Habana and came to
live in the United States

00:09:24.190 --> 00:09:26.130
when she was five years old.

00:09:26.130 --> 00:09:29.250
Her family roots through
her grandparents, however,

00:09:29.250 --> 00:09:34.070
go back to Turkey,
Poland, and Russia.

00:09:34.070 --> 00:09:37.270
She learned very
early on in her life

00:09:37.270 --> 00:09:40.490
that the world was
a very large place.

00:09:40.490 --> 00:09:44.990
She credits her bookishness to
the fact that when she was nine,

00:09:44.990 --> 00:09:50.120
going on ten, she spent an
entire year in a body cast,

00:09:50.120 --> 00:09:53.880
at which point, Ruth,
I guess you learned how

00:09:53.880 --> 00:09:56.500
to bring a large world
into a very small place.

00:09:56.500 --> 00:10:02.240
In love with books, never
without one in her hand,

00:10:02.240 --> 00:10:05.100
she studied Spanish
Literature at Wesleyan,

00:10:05.100 --> 00:10:08.460
she learned her Doctor in
Anthropology from Princeton.

00:10:08.460 --> 00:10:11.010
Her first book was based
on her dissertation

00:10:11.010 --> 00:10:13.970
about a northern
village in Spain.

00:10:13.970 --> 00:10:17.350
Her second book Translated
Woman was based on ten years

00:10:17.350 --> 00:10:20.540
of field work in a
rural town in Mexico.

00:10:20.540 --> 00:10:24.330
Her third The Vulnerable
Observer: Anthropology

00:10:24.330 --> 00:10:26.430
that Breaks your
Heart, [ininteligible]

00:10:26.430 --> 00:10:30.530
with a great title, exams
the role of the personal

00:10:30.530 --> 00:10:34.630
in her scholarly discipline,
Cultural Anthropology.

00:10:34.630 --> 00:10:39.540
Jewish Cuba is the topic of her
fourth An Island Called Home,

00:10:39.540 --> 00:10:42.220
as well as her fifth
Traveling Heavy:

00:10:42.220 --> 00:10:44.690
A Memoir in Between Journeys.

00:10:44.690 --> 00:10:47.400
Most recently she's
published a prize-winning book

00:10:47.400 --> 00:10:51.320
for young adults called Lucky
Broken Girl, and I guess that's

00:10:51.320 --> 00:10:53.890
about the body cast,
I would guess,

00:10:53.890 --> 00:10:55.800
and in fact it is, I've seen it.

00:10:55.800 --> 00:10:57.100
It's lovely.

00:10:57.100 --> 00:10:58.650
Congratulations.

00:10:58.650 --> 00:11:04.130
Just this week she was named one
of America's great immigrants

00:11:04.130 --> 00:11:06.160
by the Carnegie Foundation.

00:11:06.160 --> 00:11:09.270
According to the Carnegie
citation she is "one

00:11:09.270 --> 00:11:13.770
of America's naturalized
citizens who enriched the fabric

00:11:13.770 --> 00:11:17.420
of our culture and
strengthened our democracy

00:11:17.420 --> 00:11:21.790
through their lives, their
work, and their example."

00:11:21.790 --> 00:11:23.310
We couldn't agree more.

00:11:23.310 --> 00:11:25.510
Ladies and gentlemen,
Ruth Behar.

00:11:25.510 --> 00:11:28.510
