00:11:42.260 --> 00:11:43.560
Thank you so much.

00:11:43.560 --> 00:11:45.920
That was so beautiful,
and I am so honored.

00:11:45.920 --> 00:11:49.550
Well, it's such a huge honor
to be here today at the Library

00:11:49.550 --> 00:11:52.920
of Congress and also to
have this collaboration

00:11:52.920 --> 00:11:55.770
with the Kennedy Center
and to be un conversation

00:11:55.770 --> 00:11:58.600
with Catalina Gómez, from
the Library of Congress,

00:11:58.600 --> 00:12:01.980
and my dear friend
Rolando Estévez.

00:12:01.980 --> 00:12:06.000
So, it's really, really an
honor to be here today to talk

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:10.030
about a Cuban Love Affair,
the Art of the Book.

00:12:10.030 --> 00:12:12.610
So, before I begin, I'm going
to just say a little bit more

00:12:12.610 --> 00:12:13.910
about Rolando Estévez.

00:12:13.910 --> 00:12:15.900
We've already covered
some of his bio,

00:12:15.900 --> 00:12:18.810
but just to add a little
bit more that's important.

00:12:18.810 --> 00:12:24.530
So, Rolando Estévez, and we --
in Cuba we call him Estévez.

00:12:24.530 --> 00:12:26.270
Right? We don't call
him Rolando.

00:12:26.270 --> 00:12:28.330
His sister calls him Rolly.

00:12:28.330 --> 00:12:33.770
But in Cuba he's just known as
Estévez, people, a lot of artist

00:12:33.770 --> 00:12:35.070
in Cuba go by their last name.

00:12:35.070 --> 00:12:37.150
So, if you hear me
calling him Estévez,

00:12:37.150 --> 00:12:38.590
I'm not being disrespectful.

00:12:38.590 --> 00:12:41.870
That's the name that he uses.

00:12:41.870 --> 00:12:47.860
So Estévez was born in Matanzas
in Cuba, and he is a poet,

00:12:47.860 --> 00:12:51.840
he is a visual artist, he
works in multiple mediums,

00:12:51.840 --> 00:12:56.380
including drawing, painting,
installation, performance,

00:12:56.380 --> 00:12:57.740
and what's very important
to know is

00:12:57.740 --> 00:13:01.010
that he also does set
design for the theater,

00:13:01.010 --> 00:13:04.400
and that really informs
the way he constructs books

00:13:04.400 --> 00:13:08.150
in a very theatrical
and dramatic way.

00:13:08.150 --> 00:13:15.120
He teaches free style design and
theater design in Matanzas and,

00:13:15.120 --> 00:13:19.600
in Matanzas, he is a leading
promoter and organizer

00:13:19.600 --> 00:13:23.980
of artistic events, of
competitions, of exhibitions

00:13:23.980 --> 00:13:26.970
and other alternative
cultural activities.

00:13:26.970 --> 00:13:30.320
He really is a force
in Matanzas.

00:13:30.320 --> 00:13:36.640
And in 1985, he and the poet
Alfredo Zaldívar founded

00:13:36.640 --> 00:13:40.620
Ediciones Vigía, and all of you
I think had a chance to see some

00:13:40.620 --> 00:13:45.150
of the Ediciones Vigía books
here, and it's very interesting

00:13:45.150 --> 00:13:49.910
to understand how they
started out in 1985.

00:13:49.910 --> 00:13:53.350
Initially, their aim was
to create a welcoming space

00:13:53.350 --> 00:13:57.480
for young poets from
Matanzas, for local poets,

00:13:57.480 --> 00:14:00.120
and what they did at
the very beginning was

00:14:00.120 --> 00:14:04.190
to create beautiful
invitations to poetry readings.

00:14:04.190 --> 00:14:05.890
That was basically
how they started,

00:14:05.890 --> 00:14:08.030
and these readings
were always accompanied

00:14:08.030 --> 00:14:09.550
by a musical recital.

00:14:09.550 --> 00:14:13.130
So that was kind of the
origin of this project.

00:14:13.130 --> 00:14:14.540
They didn't have paper.

00:14:14.540 --> 00:14:15.840
This was the 80s.

00:14:15.840 --> 00:14:18.230
They didn't have paper
to make the invitations.

00:14:18.230 --> 00:14:22.540
So, they went to the local
butcher shops in Matanzas

00:14:22.540 --> 00:14:25.870
and they asked for the brown
paper from the butcher shops.

00:14:25.870 --> 00:14:28.780
And that was how they
started making these beautiful

00:14:28.780 --> 00:14:31.330
invitations on very
simple brown paper,

00:14:31.330 --> 00:14:34.910
and as you can see the brown
craft paper is still used

00:14:34.910 --> 00:14:38.970
in Estévez's new books, which
I'll talk about in a moment.

00:14:38.970 --> 00:14:43.140
So, Ediciones Vigía, important
to know that it was born

00:14:43.140 --> 00:14:47.580
in the city of Matanzas, which
is 50 miles away from Habana,

00:14:47.580 --> 00:14:51.300
and it's a city known
as "The Athens of Cuba",

00:14:51.300 --> 00:14:55.720
because there's always been
a lot of reverence for poetry

00:14:55.720 --> 00:15:00.320
and music in Matanzas, and it's
where the beautiful dance form

00:15:00.320 --> 00:15:05.070
of the danzón was born
in the city of Matanzas.

00:15:05.070 --> 00:15:10.420
And Matanzas has this historic
plaza, la Plaza de la Vigía,

00:15:10.420 --> 00:15:14.830
and it was from that plaza,
which it translates roughly into

00:15:14.830 --> 00:15:16.790
"the watchtower plaza".

00:15:16.790 --> 00:15:21.250
It was from that plaza that they
could see the ships entering the

00:15:21.250 --> 00:15:24.860
bay of Matanzas and they
could take action quickly

00:15:24.860 --> 00:15:29.140
if pirates were trying to
come and take over the city.

00:15:29.140 --> 00:15:31.150
So, this notion of
being a vigía,

00:15:31.150 --> 00:15:34.290
of watching over
things was a definition

00:15:34.290 --> 00:15:37.200
that was very important
to the co-founders

00:15:37.200 --> 00:15:41.400
of this amazing book project.

00:15:41.400 --> 00:15:44.520
And over time, Vigía
evolved, it grew bigger,

00:15:44.520 --> 00:15:48.900
it grew into a publishing house
that involved writers, designers

00:15:48.900 --> 00:15:51.950
and volunteers who
worked collaboratively

00:15:51.950 --> 00:15:55.870
to create these beautiful
handmade books.

00:15:55.870 --> 00:15:58.800
And the way it worked,
when Estévez was

00:15:58.800 --> 00:16:02.640
with Ediciones Vigía is he
would make a complete book,

00:16:02.640 --> 00:16:06.680
he would create, fabricar a
complete book, he would bring it

00:16:06.680 --> 00:16:10.120
to Vigía, and then they
would make two hundred copies

00:16:10.120 --> 00:16:14.540
of the book, and that was the
way they produced the books.

00:16:14.540 --> 00:16:19.000
And what's interesting is they
gave attention to Cuban writers

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:22.900
on the island, and you saw some
of the books in the display,

00:16:22.900 --> 00:16:27.530
like Dulce María Loynaz, Nancy
Morejón, Fina García Marruz,

00:16:27.530 --> 00:16:31.360
Miguel Barnet, all very
important Cuban writers,

00:16:31.360 --> 00:16:35.880
and always honoring José Martí,
the great independence leader

00:16:35.880 --> 00:16:41.270
and poet of Cuba, but there was
also a commitment to give space

00:16:41.270 --> 00:16:45.570
to international authors, such
as Borges or García Lorca,

00:16:45.570 --> 00:16:51.060
as you saw in the exhibit,
Borís Pasternak as well,

00:16:51.060 --> 00:16:55.320
while celebrating the work
of great American writers,

00:16:55.320 --> 00:16:57.350
such as Emily Dickinson.

00:16:57.350 --> 00:17:00.850
Y voy a hablar un
poquito del Dickinson.

00:17:00.850 --> 00:17:02.500
So, I think all of you've got

00:17:02.500 --> 00:17:07.050
to see the Emily Dickinson
book here in the display,

00:17:07.050 --> 00:17:12.990
and it's just a totally
exquisite book from 1998,

00:17:12.990 --> 00:17:15.600
and I think this is one of the
most spectacular handmade books

00:17:15.600 --> 00:17:20.180
that I have seen,
and Estévez read

00:17:20.180 --> 00:17:22.200
up on Emily Dickinson,
her biography.

00:17:22.200 --> 00:17:24.700
He knew that she was
very agoraphobic,

00:17:24.700 --> 00:17:30.510
and so he built a house for
her, for this reclusive poet,

00:17:30.510 --> 00:17:34.520
and put the poems
inside that house.

00:17:34.520 --> 00:17:39.290
At the time, Estévez had not
yet visited Dickenson's house

00:17:39.290 --> 00:17:41.330
in Amherst, which
is now a museum,

00:17:41.330 --> 00:17:45.750
but eventually he did get
to go there and he learned

00:17:45.750 --> 00:17:48.150
that the house that
he had imagined

00:17:48.150 --> 00:17:51.300
in his dreams had turned
out to be very much

00:17:51.300 --> 00:17:55.110
like the one she had
inhabited in real life.

00:17:55.110 --> 00:17:58.530
And so, the books
that he designed

00:17:58.530 --> 00:18:03.060
for Ediciones Vigía are now
collected all over the world.

00:18:03.060 --> 00:18:06.040
We have this wonderful
collection here in the Library

00:18:06.040 --> 00:18:10.370
of Congress, there are also
books in MoMA, there are books

00:18:10.370 --> 00:18:14.040
in the British Library and
I want to brag for a moment

00:18:14.040 --> 00:18:17.040
and say there are books in
many university libraries,

00:18:17.040 --> 00:18:18.880
including the University
of Michigan,

00:18:18.880 --> 00:18:22.910
and we have a very large
collection of his books

00:18:22.910 --> 00:18:26.460
in our Special Collections
Division, because the University

00:18:26.460 --> 00:18:29.680
of Michigan was the
first American university

00:18:29.680 --> 00:18:31.690
that Estévez visited,

00:18:31.690 --> 00:18:35.050
when I invited him
back in the late 90s.

00:18:35.050 --> 00:18:41.710
And, so, we began to celebrate
and to conserve these books.

00:18:41.710 --> 00:18:47.270
So, between 1985 and 2013,

00:18:47.270 --> 00:18:52.290
Estévez was the artistic
director of Ediciones Vigía,

00:18:52.290 --> 00:18:54.100
and during that time he produced

00:18:54.100 --> 00:18:59.060
over 500 gorgeous
handmade books.

00:18:59.060 --> 00:19:04.120
And it's a major contribution
to Cuban art and letters.

00:19:04.120 --> 00:19:08.470
We had an interdisciplinary
conference back in 2012,

00:19:08.470 --> 00:19:10.610
called Cultural Bricolage,

00:19:10.610 --> 00:19:15.060
organized by professor
Juanamaría Cordones-Cook,

00:19:15.060 --> 00:19:18.620
and there was so much
interest in this conference

00:19:18.620 --> 00:19:23.790
that we decided to produce an
anthology about Estévez's work

00:19:23.790 --> 00:19:27.260
for Vigía and his
work as a book artist,

00:19:27.260 --> 00:19:30.960
and I'm one of the coeditors of
this book which will be coming

00:19:30.960 --> 00:19:33.220
out next year and
it will be called

00:19:33.220 --> 00:19:37.310
or tentatively called Beautiful
Books in the Age of Technology:

00:19:37.310 --> 00:19:42.110
Rolando Estévez and the
Making of Vigía in Cuba.

00:19:42.110 --> 00:19:46.130
Today, Estévez will be
sharing his new work,

00:19:46.130 --> 00:19:50.810
and this is taking him in
very, very exciting directions.

00:19:50.810 --> 00:19:57.410
In 2013, he made the decision
to leave Ediciones Vigía

00:19:57.410 --> 00:20:01.240
and form his own imprint,
and we saw there's a few

00:20:01.240 --> 00:20:03.070
of the new books here.

00:20:03.070 --> 00:20:05.720
His new imprint is
called El Fortín.

00:20:05.720 --> 00:20:10.010
El Fortín means "the little
fort", and his plan was

00:20:10.010 --> 00:20:14.110
to be able to produce
limited edition books as well

00:20:14.110 --> 00:20:18.170
as one-of-a-kind arts books
and just to have more freedom

00:20:18.170 --> 00:20:21.460
to do his work as a book artist.

00:20:21.460 --> 00:20:26.430
An they've already gained
very, very wide recognition,

00:20:26.430 --> 00:20:30.570
and with so - Me perdonas
si estoy hablando mucho.

00:20:30.570 --> 00:20:31.870
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
No, no, para nada.

00:20:31.870 --> 00:20:33.170
Por favor, no.

00:20:33.170 --> 00:20:34.470
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: And
what's so amazing is

00:20:34.470 --> 00:20:40.060
that Estévez is now the first
licensed independent bookmaker

00:20:40.060 --> 00:20:41.360
in Cuba.

00:20:41.360 --> 00:20:42.660
All right?

00:20:42.660 --> 00:20:43.960
So, he's able to
produce these books

00:20:43.960 --> 00:20:46.100
as an independent bookmaker

00:20:46.100 --> 00:20:52.480
and he will be spearheading the
first ever artist-book pavilion

00:20:52.480 --> 00:20:55.940
at the coming bienal, art bienal

00:20:55.940 --> 00:21:00.720
that will take place
in April of 2018.

00:21:00.720 --> 00:21:05.670
And a new generation of Cuban
book artists is now being born

00:21:05.670 --> 00:21:10.210
and they are all looking
to him for inspiration.

00:21:10.210 --> 00:21:14.000
So, as you'll see today,
his creative development

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:18.770
as a bookmaker has really
inspired him to keep pushing

00:21:18.770 --> 00:21:23.290
at the limits of how to make a
book that can be called a work

00:21:23.290 --> 00:21:27.420
of art and also be a
book at the same time.

00:21:27.420 --> 00:21:32.430
And as his bookmaking has
developed, he's found new ways

00:21:32.430 --> 00:21:34.700
for words and images to speak

00:21:34.700 --> 00:21:38.840
to each other ever more
exuberantly, becoming, I think,

00:21:38.840 --> 00:21:40.160
a modern version

00:21:40.160 --> 00:21:43.130
of the illuminated
medieval manuscripts.

00:21:43.130 --> 00:21:46.220
And I think in our
era of virtual books,

00:21:46.220 --> 00:21:51.740
Estévez's work gives us all
the possibility of experiencing

00:21:51.740 --> 00:21:56.610
that tactile sensuality of
interacting with books in ways

00:21:56.610 --> 00:22:01.020
that restore to us the
wonder of the text.

00:22:01.020 --> 00:22:04.240
So, to end these remarks, I
just want to say something

00:22:04.240 --> 00:22:08.830
about my friendship
with Estévez.

00:22:08.830 --> 00:22:13.960
We met back in 1994, que
nos conocimos en el '94,

00:22:13.960 --> 00:22:17.950
so 24 years ago, we met
at the Habana book fair,

00:22:17.950 --> 00:22:21.770
and Estévez had stepped
outside to smoke a cigarette

00:22:21.770 --> 00:22:25.400
and to take a break from working
at the Ediciones Vigía stand

00:22:25.400 --> 00:22:26.700
at the Habana book fair.

00:22:26.700 --> 00:22:29.080
He was selling these postales

00:22:29.080 --> 00:22:33.270
that were essentially these
beautiful hand-painted drawings

00:22:33.270 --> 00:22:37.500
that incorporated lines of
poetry from Dulce María Loynaz.

00:22:37.500 --> 00:22:40.070
At the time, I didn't know
who Dulce María Loynaz was.

00:22:40.070 --> 00:22:45.210
She then became a huge influence
on my life, and he said to me,

00:22:45.210 --> 00:22:48.180
"Don't tell me you've
never heard of Dulce María.

00:22:48.180 --> 00:22:50.710
She's one of Cuba's
most important poets."

00:22:50.710 --> 00:22:52.940
And I said that I
hadn't heard of her.

00:22:52.940 --> 00:22:56.370
And I realized how
much I had yet to learn

00:22:56.370 --> 00:23:02.320
from Rolando Estévez about Cuban
literature, culture and history.

00:23:02.320 --> 00:23:07.260
And we struck up a
conversation back then in 1994.

00:23:07.260 --> 00:23:10.690
He was watching me intently
and I ended up telling him

00:23:10.690 --> 00:23:15.020
that I was this cubana who was
returning to the island looking

00:23:15.020 --> 00:23:17.260
for my roots, I was
speaking to him of my need

00:23:17.260 --> 00:23:21.110
to return even though my parents
didn't want me to travel to Cuba

00:23:21.110 --> 00:23:22.500
and in fact they've
never been back,

00:23:22.500 --> 00:23:26.310
and he nodded very
sympathetically and then he said

00:23:26.310 --> 00:23:29.690
that I reminded him
of his younger sister.

00:23:29.690 --> 00:23:33.230
She was an eight-year-old
girl when she left Cuba

00:23:33.230 --> 00:23:35.320
with their parents in 1969.

00:23:35.320 --> 00:23:38.800
He had not seen her
in all that time.

00:23:38.800 --> 00:23:43.170
He'd not been able to leave
because he was 15 and considered

00:23:43.170 --> 00:23:46.310
of military age by Cuban law.

00:23:46.310 --> 00:23:51.300
So, he knew in his own flesh how
immigration could cut both ways,

00:23:51.300 --> 00:23:54.480
producing grief for
those leaving as well

00:23:54.480 --> 00:23:57.080
as for those waving goodbye.

00:23:57.080 --> 00:23:59.790
And after our conversation,
Estévez said

00:23:59.790 --> 00:24:01.540
that I should go
inside and have a look

00:24:01.540 --> 00:24:04.610
at the Ediciones Vigía books,
and I said to him, "But,

00:24:04.610 --> 00:24:05.910
how will I find them?"

00:24:05.910 --> 00:24:08.530
And he said, "Oh,
you'll find them.

00:24:08.530 --> 00:24:09.830
You won't be able to miss them."

00:24:09.830 --> 00:24:13.150
And he lit up another
cigarette and I went inside,

00:24:13.150 --> 00:24:16.290
and I walk through this
dark hall, seeing just a lot

00:24:16.290 --> 00:24:19.930
of gloomy-looking books printed
by the government presses,

00:24:19.930 --> 00:24:22.560
and I said, "Where do I
find Ediciones Vigía?"

00:24:22.560 --> 00:24:26.340
And then I saw this tall
palm tree and it was made

00:24:26.340 --> 00:24:29.030
of the brown butcher
paper, very tall palm tree,

00:24:29.030 --> 00:24:32.960
the tree of course had been
designed and built by Estévez.

00:24:32.960 --> 00:24:37.460
And he was right,
it was impossible

00:24:37.460 --> 00:24:40.690
to miss these beautiful books.

00:24:40.690 --> 00:24:43.050
They were all fashioned
from simple brown paper,

00:24:43.050 --> 00:24:46.680
were handmade, hand-colored,
hand-printed, hand-bound,

00:24:46.680 --> 00:24:49.390
and I didn't know what to
make of these creations,

00:24:49.390 --> 00:24:52.600
but I fell in love
with them immediately.

00:24:52.600 --> 00:24:56.210
And so began my Cuban love
affair with the artist

00:24:56.210 --> 00:25:01.110
of the book and especially with
the art of Estévez's books.

00:25:01.110 --> 00:25:04.900
So honored and so thrilled
to be here, and with that,

00:25:04.900 --> 00:25:06.200
I don't know if I'll move

00:25:06.200 --> 00:25:10.250
to Catalina Gómez o move
toward our conversation

00:25:10.250 --> 00:25:11.550
with Rolando Estévez.

00:25:11.550 --> 00:25:12.980
&gt;&gt; Catalina Gómez: I think
it should be Rolando Estévez.

00:25:12.980 --> 00:25:14.280
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Thank
you so much.

00:25:14.280 --> 00:25:16.080
[risa]

00:25:16.080 --> 00:25:19.040
[ Aplausos ]

00:25:19.040 --> 00:25:20.340
&gt;&gt; Catalina Gómez: I
think you should --

00:25:20.340 --> 00:25:21.640
I should be at the end.

00:25:21.640 --> 00:25:22.980
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: You
should be at the end.

00:25:22.980 --> 00:25:24.280
&gt;&gt; Catalina Gómez: I think, yes.

00:25:24.280 --> 00:25:25.580
&gt;&gt; Ruth Gómez: Okay.

00:25:25.580 --> 00:25:26.880
&gt;&gt; Catalina Gómez:
[ininteligible] the stars.

00:25:26.880 --> 00:25:28.180
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, we'll
start with -- we're going --

00:25:28.180 --> 00:25:29.480
we have several books
that we want to show you,

00:25:29.480 --> 00:25:32.770
and discuss with you, and
I will be both interacting

00:25:32.770 --> 00:25:36.070
and translating as
well from Spanish.

00:25:36.070 --> 00:25:37.370
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
¿Quieres comentar alguno -- ?

00:25:37.370 --> 00:25:38.840
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Eh,
no, vamos a empezar.

00:25:38.840 --> 00:25:41.110
Yo creo que yay o he
hablado demasiado.

00:25:41.110 --> 00:25:42.410
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Ya.

00:25:42.410 --> 00:25:43.710
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Sí, sí.

00:25:43.710 --> 00:25:45.010
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Voy a empezar.

00:25:45.010 --> 00:25:47.180
Bueno, quiero empezar mostrando,
darle las gracias a Ruth por --

00:25:47.180 --> 00:25:49.660
y a la Biblioteca del
Congreso, sobre todo,

00:25:49.660 --> 00:25:53.970
por esta oportunidad y por
cuánto me emociona ver esos

00:25:53.970 --> 00:25:56.680
libros de Vigía y El Fortín
ahí, en esta exposición.

00:25:56.680 --> 00:25:59.490
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, he wants to
say thank you so much to all

00:25:59.490 --> 00:26:01.200
of us for being here,
the two of us,

00:26:01.200 --> 00:26:05.490
and how incredibly moved
he is to see the books here

00:26:05.490 --> 00:26:08.720
at the Library of Congress,
and so beautifully conserved.

00:26:08.720 --> 00:26:11.480
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Quiero decir
primero que El Fortín es mi

00:26:11.480 --> 00:26:14.810
continuación como artista
en el mundo del libro.

00:26:14.810 --> 00:26:19.720
Empecé, fundé Vigía junto a
Alfredo Zaldívar en el '85.

00:26:19.720 --> 00:26:22.880
Estuve 28 años y
más en ese lugar.

00:26:22.880 --> 00:26:26.500
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, El Fortín
is a continuation of the work

00:26:26.500 --> 00:26:29.190
that he began at
Ediciones Vigía.

00:26:29.190 --> 00:26:33.070
He worked with Zaldívar,
the cofounder, for 28 years

00:26:33.070 --> 00:26:36.460
and now is continuing
the work with El Fortín.

00:26:36.460 --> 00:26:38.160
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: El
Fortín es mi propio Proyecto.

00:26:38.160 --> 00:26:41.920
Ya en Cuba puede haber un
proyecto privado de libros.

00:26:41.920 --> 00:26:44.590
Fui el primero, ya lo dijiste.

00:26:44.590 --> 00:26:45.890
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Sí.

00:26:45.890 --> 00:26:47.190
So, El Fortín, again,

00:26:47.190 --> 00:26:49.780
is the first independent
bookmaking project.

00:26:49.780 --> 00:26:51.080
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:

00:26:51.080 --> 00:26:52.980
Y este Fortín me da la
posibilidad de continuar mi

00:26:52.980 --> 00:26:55.370
trabajo como diseñador
de libros,

00:26:55.370 --> 00:26:58.930
añandiendo ahora el
trabajo de los libros arte,

00:26:58.930 --> 00:27:00.470
los ejemplares únicos.

00:27:00.470 --> 00:27:03.360
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, El Fortín
allows him to keep doing books

00:27:03.360 --> 00:27:07.010
in small series while at
the same time being able

00:27:07.010 --> 00:27:09.810
to make one-of-a-kind
unique artists' books.

00:27:09.810 --> 00:27:11.110
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:

00:27:11.110 --> 00:27:17.360
Quiero empezar mostrándoles este
libro que es un poster de Alejo

00:27:17.360 --> 00:27:19.270
Galván, un poeta de la ciudad.

00:27:19.270 --> 00:27:21.300
Vamos a zafarlo aquí.

00:27:21.300 --> 00:27:25.620
Estos libros llevan
una interacción.

00:27:25.620 --> 00:27:27.920
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: His books require
quite a lot of interaction.

00:27:27.920 --> 00:27:34.160
This is a book of poems,
three poems by Alejo Galván,

00:27:34.160 --> 00:27:38.490
a poet from Matanzas, and it's
called La Tarde, The Afternoon.

00:27:38.490 --> 00:27:40.960
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Se me hizo
un nudito aquí, momentico.

00:27:40.960 --> 00:27:42.260
Ya.

00:27:42.260 --> 00:27:44.560
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Ya está.

00:27:47.040 --> 00:27:50.330
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Este poster
contiene tres poemas de Alejo

00:27:50.330 --> 00:27:53.800
Galván, poemas dedicados a
la ciudad de los puentes y

00:27:53.800 --> 00:27:55.100
los ríos.

00:27:55.100 --> 00:27:58.480
Aquí están las imágenes
de la ciudad.

00:27:58.480 --> 00:28:00.550
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, these
are three poems that are all

00:28:00.550 --> 00:28:04.030
about the city of Matanzas,
and Matanzas is a city

00:28:04.030 --> 00:28:07.360
of three rivers, and the
ocean, and many bridges,

00:28:07.360 --> 00:28:10.590
and so he captures
that in the artwork.

00:28:10.590 --> 00:28:14.350
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: En la cabeza
de esta mujer que es como la

00:28:14.350 --> 00:28:15.650
ciudad, el lighthouse.

00:28:15.650 --> 00:28:17.340
Me encanta la palabra en inglés.

00:28:17.340 --> 00:28:22.550
El faro, que es el símbolo
de Ediciones El Fortín.

00:28:22.550 --> 00:28:24.910
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, the
lighthouse is the symbol

00:28:24.910 --> 00:28:27.700
of El Fortín, of his
imprint El Fortín.

00:28:27.700 --> 00:28:29.890
And he mentioned that
there's a lighthouse coming

00:28:29.890 --> 00:28:31.980
out of the head of the woman,

00:28:31.980 --> 00:28:33.940
and he loves that
word in English.

00:28:33.940 --> 00:28:36.440
So, he tends to say
"lighthouse" rather than "faro",

00:28:36.440 --> 00:28:38.880
which is the word in Spanish.

00:28:38.880 --> 00:28:40.180
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Por la parte de atrás,

00:28:40.180 --> 00:28:42.560
las informaciones sobre
la cantidad de ejemplares,

00:28:42.560 --> 00:28:45.300
sobre el poeta, en fin.

00:28:45.300 --> 00:28:47.970
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, he includes
information about the poet,

00:28:47.970 --> 00:28:50.200
the number of copies
that were made.

00:28:50.200 --> 00:28:54.270
So, all of that information is
always included in each book.

00:28:54.270 --> 00:28:55.570
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Pequeñas notas,

00:28:55.570 --> 00:28:59.520
pequeñas sorpresas que
siempre tienen estos libros.

00:28:59.520 --> 00:29:01.340
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Notes and
surprises, as he said,

00:29:01.340 --> 00:29:04.030
the books always
contain surprises.

00:29:04.030 --> 00:29:05.330
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
En este caso,

00:29:05.330 --> 00:29:07.960
una nota sobre el
poeta, sobre el autor.

00:29:10.230 --> 00:29:12.950
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, there's a
note there about the author.

00:29:14.040 --> 00:29:16.060
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:

00:29:16.060 --> 00:29:18.090
[ Inaudible ]

00:29:18.090 --> 00:29:19.390
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Entonces,

00:29:19.390 --> 00:29:20.990
ese es un libro que es un
libro como poster, tú decías.

00:29:20.990 --> 00:29:22.290
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Como poster, sí.

00:29:22.290 --> 00:29:23.590
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Como poster.

00:29:23.590 --> 00:29:24.890
So, it's like a book-poster.

00:29:24.890 --> 00:29:27.690
Y la idea de poder también,
o sea, tenerlo en la pared,

00:29:27.690 --> 00:29:28.990
como arte, como obre de arte.

00:29:28.990 --> 00:29:30.600
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Sí, están
hechos exactamente para eso,

00:29:30.600 --> 00:29:34.240
para poder leerlos, interactuar
con ellos o tenerlos en una

00:29:34.240 --> 00:29:36.910
pared, como se pone un
cuadro, como se pone un cartel.

00:29:36.910 --> 00:29:38.210
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Ahá.

00:29:38.210 --> 00:29:40.070
So, the idea of being able to
interact with the book, read it,

00:29:40.070 --> 00:29:42.410
but you can also hang
it up and enjoy it

00:29:42.410 --> 00:29:44.500
as a work of art as well.

00:29:44.500 --> 00:29:45.800
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: ¿Seguimos?

00:29:45.800 --> 00:29:47.100
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Seguimos, eh --

00:29:47.100 --> 00:29:48.400
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Eliseo.

00:29:48.400 --> 00:29:49.700
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Eliseo.

00:29:49.700 --> 00:29:51.730
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Este es un
poeta que no vive en la ciudad

00:29:51.730 --> 00:29:53.320
de Matanzas.

00:29:53.320 --> 00:29:58.040
Eh, este es un poeta que vive en
una pequeña ciudad del sur de la

00:29:58.040 --> 00:30:00.770
provincial que se
llama Jovellanos,

00:30:00.770 --> 00:30:06.400
un pueblo donde hay mucha
cultura negra, afrocubana,

00:30:06.400 --> 00:30:09.770
un asentamiento muy grande de
esclavos hubo en ese lugar.

00:30:09.770 --> 00:30:11.070
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Déjame traducir.

00:30:11.070 --> 00:30:12.370
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Sí.

00:30:12.370 --> 00:30:14.410
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, this poet,
Eliseo Abreu Hernández is

00:30:14.410 --> 00:30:18.470
from the province of Matanzas,
from the town of Jovellanos,

00:30:18.470 --> 00:30:20.660
where there was and
continues to be a very,

00:30:20.660 --> 00:30:24.150
very important Afro-Cuban
presence, culture and religious

00:30:24.150 --> 00:30:27.110
and spiritual presence, and
that's where this poet is from.

00:30:27.110 --> 00:30:30.810
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Este hombre
ganó el concurso Digdora Alonso,

00:30:30.810 --> 00:30:35.480
que es un concurso de poesía
que tiene Ediciones El Fortín.

00:30:35.480 --> 00:30:37.790
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So,
he has a competition,

00:30:37.790 --> 00:30:42.810
a poetry competition each year
at El Fortín and this poet won,

00:30:42.810 --> 00:30:46.020
and therefore his book was
published in El Fortín.

00:30:46.020 --> 00:30:47.900
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Es un
libro también bilingüe.

00:30:47.900 --> 00:30:51.180
Casi todos los libros del
Fortín son o bilingües o

00:30:51.180 --> 00:30:54.730
trilingües, porque es una
manera en que más personas

00:30:54.730 --> 00:30:57.120
pueden llegar a leer el libro.

00:30:57.120 --> 00:30:59.450
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, this book
is bilingual, and he tries

00:30:59.450 --> 00:31:02.740
to have his El Fortín
books bilingual

00:31:02.740 --> 00:31:04.350
and sometimes even trilingual,

00:31:04.350 --> 00:31:07.070
so that more people can
have access to these texts.

00:31:07.070 --> 00:31:09.630
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: La bolsa es
como una pequeña mochila que se

00:31:09.630 --> 00:31:11.220
pudiera llevar aquí al hombre.

00:31:11.220 --> 00:31:13.270
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: [Risa] Probably
doesn't need translation,

00:31:13.270 --> 00:31:15.670
but the idea that it's
almost a little knapsack

00:31:15.670 --> 00:31:17.290
and you can carry it with you.

00:31:17.290 --> 00:31:18.590
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Este es un poeta fuerte,

00:31:18.590 --> 00:31:20.150
enérgico, con poemas muy --

00:31:20.150 --> 00:31:21.710
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: This is a
very, very strong poet.

00:31:21.710 --> 00:31:23.230
Y este poeta está enfermo, ¿no?

00:31:23.230 --> 00:31:25.320
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Está
enfermo, enfermo de cáncer.

00:31:25.320 --> 00:31:26.620
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: He's
suffering from --

00:31:26.620 --> 00:31:28.750
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Y toda
su poesía está llena de esa

00:31:28.750 --> 00:31:31.890
imploración que hace a la vida
por que le siga dando salud y es

00:31:31.890 --> 00:31:35.020
una poesía que también
habla del dolor físico y del

00:31:35.020 --> 00:31:36.320
dolor espiritual.

00:31:36.320 --> 00:31:38.850
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, he is a poet
who is suffering from cancer.

00:31:38.850 --> 00:31:42.210
So, his poems have a lot to
do with physical suffering,

00:31:42.210 --> 00:31:46.160
searching for healing, those
are themes in his work.

00:31:46.160 --> 00:31:48.460
Seguimos.

00:31:50.080 --> 00:31:51.380
La zafra.

00:31:51.380 --> 00:31:52.680
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: La Zafra.

00:31:52.680 --> 00:31:53.980
Este es un libro que
me gusta especialmente.

00:31:53.980 --> 00:31:56.600
Es un libro, La Zafra
de Agustín Acosta.

00:31:56.600 --> 00:32:00.670
Agustín Acosta fue poeta
nacional en Cuba antes que

00:32:00.670 --> 00:32:02.460
Nicolás Guillén.

00:32:02.460 --> 00:32:06.280
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, this is
a book by Agustín Acosta.

00:32:06.280 --> 00:32:09.700
This is a poet who lived
outside of Cuba, in Miami,

00:32:09.700 --> 00:32:12.230
but before he left
Cuba, he was Cuba --

00:32:12.230 --> 00:32:16.400
he was declared Cuba's National
Poet, before Nicolás Guillén.

00:32:16.400 --> 00:32:18.300
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Pero hay
algo que es bien interesante.

00:32:18.300 --> 00:32:22.620
Se fue de Cuba y perdió su
condición de poeta nacional y se

00:32:22.620 --> 00:32:26.160
nombró a otro poeta nacional
en Cuba, estando vivo Agustín,

00:32:26.160 --> 00:32:27.460
que fue Nicolás Guillén.

00:32:27.460 --> 00:32:28.760
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Right.

00:32:28.760 --> 00:32:30.560
So, he was Cuba's Nactional
Poet, but after he left Cuba,

00:32:30.560 --> 00:32:34.110
he was no longer Cuba's
National Poet, and that was

00:32:34.110 --> 00:32:36.310
when Nicolás Guillén was named.

00:32:36.310 --> 00:32:37.610
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:

00:32:37.610 --> 00:32:40.210
En los oscuros tiempos de los
'70 y las parametraciones,

00:32:40.210 --> 00:32:41.970
este fue un poeta
prohibido en Cuba,

00:32:41.970 --> 00:32:44.450
un poeta que había
abandonado el país.

00:32:44.450 --> 00:32:47.010
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, this
is a poet that in the 70s,

00:32:47.010 --> 00:32:50.680
which is a very dark period in
Cuban history, it was impossible

00:32:50.680 --> 00:32:52.560
to read this poet's work.

00:32:52.560 --> 00:32:55.970
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Escribió en
la década del 30 su gran libro,

00:32:55.970 --> 00:32:59.130
La Zafra, y esta es
tapa la que contiene.

00:32:59.130 --> 00:33:02.120
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: This is one
of his great books, La Zafra.

00:33:02.120 --> 00:33:03.480
Is the sugar cane harvest.

00:33:03.480 --> 00:33:05.600
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Algunos
de los poemas de ese libro

00:33:05.600 --> 00:33:06.900
La Zafra.

00:33:06.900 --> 00:33:10.800
Está realizada la cubierta
en caña de azúcar, prensada.

00:33:10.800 --> 00:33:15.440
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So the cover
has pressed sugar cane.

00:33:15.440 --> 00:33:16.740
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Fibras naturales.

00:33:16.740 --> 00:33:18.040
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Natural fibers.

00:33:18.040 --> 00:33:19.770
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Para dar
toda la atmósfera del campo.

00:33:19.770 --> 00:33:22.680
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: And this
is a selection of poems

00:33:22.680 --> 00:33:26.000
from this book La Zafra,
The Sugar Cane Harvest.

00:33:26.000 --> 00:33:29.780
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Y aquí
están los dibujos de la portada,

00:33:29.780 --> 00:33:32.380
de la portadilla, está
muy lleno de dibujos.

00:33:32.380 --> 00:33:35.680
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, it has a lot
of images, a lot of drawings.

00:33:35.680 --> 00:33:40.350
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Cada poema
está precedido de un dibujo,

00:33:40.350 --> 00:33:42.520
especialmente hecho para él.

00:33:42.520 --> 00:33:45.970
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, each poem is
accompanied by an illustration.

00:33:50.120 --> 00:33:51.820
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Hasta
llegar así al final del libro.

00:33:51.820 --> 00:33:55.110
Y otra cosa interesante
es que la bolsa,

00:33:55.110 --> 00:34:02.210
esta bolsa está hecha con los
sacos que se usan en Cuba para

00:34:02.210 --> 00:34:05.400
exportar, para comercializar
el azúcar.

00:34:05.400 --> 00:34:07.090
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, he used

00:34:07.090 --> 00:34:10.240
for this book an actual
bag that's used --

00:34:10.240 --> 00:34:14.460
these are the actual bags or
sacks that are used in Cuba

00:34:14.460 --> 00:34:16.250
to transport sugar, so --

00:34:16.250 --> 00:34:19.850
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Es una cosa
que he tenido siempre presente

00:34:19.850 --> 00:34:21.780
en estos libros y
también en los únicos,

00:34:21.780 --> 00:34:25.480
es que el material se tiene
que convertir en un contenido

00:34:25.480 --> 00:34:26.780
del libro.

00:34:26.780 --> 00:34:29.160
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, this has
always been very much the case

00:34:29.160 --> 00:34:32.220
in his books, that the
container of the book has

00:34:32.220 --> 00:34:35.330
to be part of the book as well.

00:34:35.330 --> 00:34:36.630
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Mm-hm.

00:34:36.630 --> 00:34:37.930
¿Seguimos?

00:34:37.930 --> 00:34:39.230
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Seguimos.

00:34:39.230 --> 00:34:40.680
Una flor debajo de la bota.

00:34:40.680 --> 00:34:43.080
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Este
es un pequeño libro mío,

00:34:43.080 --> 00:34:47.010
una pequeña plaquette, un libro
con un poema llamado Una flor

00:34:47.010 --> 00:34:48.800
debajo de la bota.

00:34:48.800 --> 00:34:51.760
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, this is
a plaquette, a small book

00:34:51.760 --> 00:34:55.370
with a poem that
Estévez himself wrote,

00:34:55.370 --> 00:34:57.880
A Flower Beneath the Boot.

00:34:57.880 --> 00:34:59.940
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Es un
poema en contra de la Guerra,

00:34:59.940 --> 00:35:01.240
por supuesto.

00:35:01.240 --> 00:35:02.540
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: It's
an antiwar poem.

00:35:02.540 --> 00:35:04.410
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Que habla de
las botas militares que aplastan

00:35:04.410 --> 00:35:05.710
los campos.

00:35:05.710 --> 00:35:07.670
&gt;&gt; Ruth Estévez: That
talks about military boots

00:35:07.670 --> 00:35:10.610
that squash the fields
and flower fields.

00:35:10.610 --> 00:35:12.840
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Una sillita
que es como la espera de cuándo

00:35:12.840 --> 00:35:14.830
van a pasar estos
tiempos de guerra.

00:35:14.830 --> 00:35:18.000
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: This is a
chair indicating waiting

00:35:18.000 --> 00:35:22.640
when these times of war
are going to pass and end.

00:35:22.640 --> 00:35:25.370
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Aquí
hay una nota sobre el poeta.

00:35:25.370 --> 00:35:26.890
Aquí está.

00:35:26.890 --> 00:35:28.500
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: A little
note about the author

00:35:28.500 --> 00:35:31.350
of the poem, there's the poem.

00:35:31.350 --> 00:35:34.010
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Un poema en español.

00:35:34.010 --> 00:35:36.550
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: The
poem in Spanish.

00:35:36.550 --> 00:35:37.850
Y está en inglés.

00:35:37.850 --> 00:35:39.150
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Y está en inglés.

00:35:39.150 --> 00:35:40.450
Y está por detrás --

00:35:40.450 --> 00:35:41.900
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: And then
behind it is the English --

00:35:41.900 --> 00:35:43.200
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
El poema en inglés.

00:35:43.200 --> 00:35:44.500
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: The
English translation.

00:35:44.500 --> 00:35:45.820
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Estas son
impresiones directas de una bota

00:35:45.820 --> 00:35:49.630
military sobre el
papel floreado.

00:35:49.630 --> 00:35:51.320
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, he
used an actual footprint

00:35:51.320 --> 00:35:52.620
or imprint of a boot here.

00:35:52.620 --> 00:35:53.920
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:

00:35:53.920 --> 00:35:55.220
Hecho directamente con
la bota de un hombre,

00:35:55.220 --> 00:35:56.520
una impression directa.

00:35:56.520 --> 00:35:57.820
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Made
directly with a man's boot.

00:35:57.820 --> 00:35:59.120
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Y
por detrás hay retazos de

00:35:59.120 --> 00:36:00.420
uniformes militares.

00:36:00.420 --> 00:36:01.720
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: And it's
got bits and pieces

00:36:01.720 --> 00:36:04.020
of military uniforms here.

00:36:11.250 --> 00:36:12.550
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Okay.

00:36:12.550 --> 00:36:15.680
Este es el símbolo de
ediciones El Fortín,

00:36:15.680 --> 00:36:19.290
es un cuño que tengo para estos
libros y siempre está en esta

00:36:19.290 --> 00:36:24.250
página el cuño, el número
del ejemplar y la firma.

00:36:24.250 --> 00:36:26.990
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, this is
a special stamp that it has,

00:36:26.990 --> 00:36:29.120
again, symbolizing
the lighthouse,

00:36:29.120 --> 00:36:32.600
is the symbol of El Fortín.

00:36:32.600 --> 00:36:33.900
¿Seguimos?

00:36:33.900 --> 00:36:35.200
Bolero [initeligible].

00:36:35.200 --> 00:36:36.500
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Ah, Bueno.

00:36:36.500 --> 00:36:38.960
Este es un libro muy especial
para mí, es de un gran amigo.

00:36:38.960 --> 00:36:41.460
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: This is a
special book, this is of --

00:36:41.460 --> 00:36:42.850
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Gran
músico, Lázaro Horta.

00:36:42.850 --> 00:36:46.780
&gt;&gt; Ruth Baher: A friend of his,
Lázaro Horta, who is a musician.

00:36:46.780 --> 00:36:49.520
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Vive en
Miami hace más de 20 años.

00:36:49.520 --> 00:36:52.340
&gt;&gt; Ruth Baher: He's been living
in Miami for more than 20 years.

00:36:52.340 --> 00:36:53.640
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:

00:36:53.640 --> 00:36:55.760
Ha ido constantemente a Matanzas
a cantar y pasó una cosa

00:36:55.760 --> 00:36:57.060
muy curiosa.

00:36:57.060 --> 00:36:59.310
Este año, al principio, fue y,

00:36:59.310 --> 00:37:00.720
como no llevaba una
visa cultural,

00:37:00.720 --> 00:37:02.810
no lo permitieron
cantar en Matanzas.

00:37:02.810 --> 00:37:04.350
&gt;&gt; Ruth Baher: Ahá, wow.

00:37:04.350 --> 00:37:07.390
So, he goes back, he's from
Matanzas as well, Lázaro Horta,

00:37:07.390 --> 00:37:10.510
his friend, and he goes back
all the time to, you know,

00:37:10.510 --> 00:37:12.030
to visit, to be there.

00:37:12.030 --> 00:37:14.640
But this past year,
he went to Matanzas

00:37:14.640 --> 00:37:16.450
and he didn't have
a cultural visa

00:37:16.450 --> 00:37:19.490
and they didn't let him
sing in his hometown.

00:37:19.490 --> 00:37:21.310
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Este
libro tiene cinco canciones de

00:37:21.310 --> 00:37:22.610
Lázaro Horta.

00:37:22.610 --> 00:37:24.010
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, this
book has five songs.

00:37:24.010 --> 00:37:25.950
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: La herradura
viene por el último poema,

00:37:25.950 --> 00:37:30.650
la última canción que se llama
"¿Dónde están los caballos?"

00:37:30.650 --> 00:37:34.370
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: And this
symbol here is for a poem,

00:37:34.370 --> 00:37:36.790
one of the last poems, which
is about where are the horses.

00:37:36.790 --> 00:37:38.800
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: El
dibujo que se desplaza,

00:37:38.800 --> 00:37:40.660
completamente todo
iluminado a mano.

00:37:40.660 --> 00:37:42.570
Ahí no hay color
impreso en ninguno.

00:37:42.570 --> 00:37:44.410
&gt;&gt; Ruth Baher: So that
lovely illustration.

00:37:44.410 --> 00:37:45.710
Enséñalo otra vez.

00:37:45.710 --> 00:37:50.360
That lovely illustration is
all hand-done and hand-painted.

00:37:50.360 --> 00:37:52.030
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Esta piedra
es recogida en el barrio de

00:37:52.030 --> 00:37:57.440
Pueblo Nuevo, el barrio donde
nació y creció Lázaro Horta.

00:37:57.440 --> 00:37:58.780
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So,
there's a stone there

00:37:58.780 --> 00:38:00.510
from the neighborhood
of Pueblo Nuevo,

00:38:00.510 --> 00:38:02.540
which is where Lázaro
Horta is from.

00:38:02.540 --> 00:38:05.900
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Y todos
estos detalles se aclaran.

00:38:05.900 --> 00:38:10.700
Siempre, en cada libro de El
Fortín, en el machón o colofón.

00:38:10.700 --> 00:38:13.050
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, all of
these details about the book

00:38:13.050 --> 00:38:14.350
and how it was [ininteligible].

00:38:14.350 --> 00:38:15.650
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:

00:38:15.650 --> 00:38:16.950
Ahí se aclara todos esos
detalles de la Piedra,

00:38:16.950 --> 00:38:18.250
la cantidad de ejemplares,

00:38:18.250 --> 00:38:21.030
que la iluminación es
completamente manual, en fin.

00:38:21.030 --> 00:38:23.630
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: All the
information, things like the use

00:38:23.630 --> 00:38:25.890
of the stone, the way that
things were colored in,

00:38:25.890 --> 00:38:28.900
all of that information is
at the end of the books.

00:38:28.900 --> 00:38:31.590
So, the story of the book
is included with the book.

00:38:31.590 --> 00:38:32.890
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Distintos papeles,

00:38:32.890 --> 00:38:36.610
distintos tipos de
letra, el piano presente,

00:38:36.610 --> 00:38:40.220
que es el instrument que
lo acompaña en la música.

00:38:40.220 --> 00:38:43.520
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Different kinds
of paper, different kinds

00:38:43.520 --> 00:38:47.180
of print, images, and then the
piano is there as a symbol,

00:38:47.180 --> 00:38:49.320
since that is Lázaro's
instrument.

00:38:49.320 --> 00:38:53.180
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Muchos
dibujos, la nota introductoria,

00:38:53.180 --> 00:38:56.930
un bolero sin fin,
una ilustración,

00:38:56.930 --> 00:39:00.030
un dibujo para cada
una de las canciones.

00:39:00.030 --> 00:39:02.110
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, an
illustration for each song,

00:39:02.110 --> 00:39:05.120
and "Bolero sin fin"
means "endless bolero",

00:39:05.120 --> 00:39:06.420
a bolero that doesn't end.

00:39:06.420 --> 00:39:08.930
Boleros are the beautiful love
songs that come [ininteligible].

00:39:08.930 --> 00:39:10.750
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Cada una de
las canciones tiene también la

00:39:10.750 --> 00:39:14.610
música manuscrita por el
músico, por Lázaro Horta,

00:39:14.610 --> 00:39:16.710
y que después yo reproduje,

00:39:16.710 --> 00:39:19.240
pero están manuscritas y
firmadas por el músico.

00:39:19.240 --> 00:39:22.080
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: He also
included these manuscript copies

00:39:22.080 --> 00:39:25.920
of the actual musical
notations of Lázaro.

00:39:25.920 --> 00:39:27.220
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Así,

00:39:27.220 --> 00:39:30.880
cada cancion tiene un dibujo que
está lleno de la atmósfera de

00:39:30.880 --> 00:39:34.340
cada cancion, igual su música.

00:39:34.340 --> 00:39:38.210
Y así, las cinco canciones.

00:39:38.210 --> 00:39:40.640
Este es el marcador,
marca el libro.

00:39:40.640 --> 00:39:42.200
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, the
five -- ¿Te ayudo?

00:39:42.200 --> 00:39:43.500
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Sí, ábrelo.

00:39:43.500 --> 00:39:47.100
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: The
five songs and then --

00:39:47.100 --> 00:39:48.420
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Este piano con alas.

00:39:48.420 --> 00:39:50.840
Este piano con alas
que está aquí.

00:39:50.840 --> 00:39:52.140
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Ahá.

00:39:52.140 --> 00:39:55.040
The piano with wings.

00:39:55.040 --> 00:39:56.340
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
¿Dónde están los caballos?

00:39:56.340 --> 00:39:58.320
La cancion que cierra
el libro, con su dibujo.

00:39:58.320 --> 00:40:00.090
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: The closing
song is Where are the Horses?

00:40:00.090 --> 00:40:03.760
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Y también
la música y después, bueno,

00:40:03.760 --> 00:40:08.540
las informaciones que dan el
machón, el índice y todo esos --

00:40:08.540 --> 00:40:10.170
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: And all the
information at the end, again,

00:40:10.170 --> 00:40:13.970
about the book and how is made
and the elements that were used.

00:40:16.600 --> 00:40:17.900
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Okay.

00:40:17.900 --> 00:40:19.200
Seguimos.

00:40:19.200 --> 00:40:21.500
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Seguimos.

00:40:22.700 --> 00:40:25.580
Okay. Los cinco poemas del mar.

00:40:25.580 --> 00:40:27.930
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Cinco
poemas del mar y de la soledad.

00:40:29.070 --> 00:40:30.490
A ver cómo pongo
esto para que --

00:40:30.490 --> 00:40:32.790
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: ¿Te ayudo?

00:40:34.380 --> 00:40:36.680
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Ya.

00:40:38.350 --> 00:40:42.330
Cinco poemas del mar y de
la Soledad es otro de los

00:40:42.330 --> 00:40:46.970
acercamientos que ha hecho
Ediciones El Fortín --

00:40:51.150 --> 00:40:55.480
A la obra de Ruth Behar y a la
Amistad que nos une en el arte,

00:40:55.480 --> 00:40:59.060
sobre todo, es una amistad que
tiene mucha entraña artística,

00:40:59.060 --> 00:41:02.660
mucha entraña literaria
y plástica.

00:41:02.660 --> 00:41:03.960
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Ay, gracias.

00:41:03.960 --> 00:41:07.500
So, this book is a
collaboration between us, again,

00:41:07.500 --> 00:41:14.150
part of our long friendship and
interconnection of our lives

00:41:14.150 --> 00:41:17.110
and artistic work as well.

00:41:17.110 --> 00:41:18.410
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
También tiene una bosa.

00:41:18.410 --> 00:41:20.560
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: It also
comes with a special bag.

00:41:20.560 --> 00:41:24.260
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: El libro
se llama Poemas del mar y de

00:41:24.260 --> 00:41:25.560
la Soledad.

00:41:25.560 --> 00:41:28.230
Tiene esta imagen de
la Virgen de Regla.

00:41:28.230 --> 00:41:29.920
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So,
it's called Five Poems

00:41:29.920 --> 00:41:31.420
About the Sea and Solitude.

00:41:31.420 --> 00:41:33.660
It has an image of
the Virgin of Regla.

00:41:33.660 --> 00:41:34.960
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:

00:41:34.960 --> 00:41:36.670
Que sincretiza nuestras
religiones con Yemayá,

00:41:36.670 --> 00:41:40.010
que es la dueña del
mar, la orisha del mar.

00:41:40.010 --> 00:41:43.220
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Which, the Virgin
of Regla syncretize with Yemayá,

00:41:43.220 --> 00:41:46.050
who is de deity of the
ocean, of the sea, very,

00:41:46.050 --> 00:41:48.040
very important in Cuba.

00:41:48.040 --> 00:41:49.600
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Tiene siete conchas.

00:41:49.600 --> 00:41:51.720
El siete es el número de Yemayá.

00:41:51.720 --> 00:41:53.020
El siete.

00:41:53.020 --> 00:41:54.320
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: And she
has seven seashells,

00:41:54.320 --> 00:41:55.800
because this is her number.

00:41:55.800 --> 00:41:57.890
This is Yemaya's number.

00:41:57.890 --> 00:42:01.430
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Cualquier
papel hermoso sirve para

00:42:01.430 --> 00:42:05.050
trabajar en esta editorial.

00:42:05.050 --> 00:42:08.310
Esto es unas servilletas
que encontré en una parte,

00:42:08.310 --> 00:42:13.310
en un lugar del mundo y
me parecieron perfectas.

00:42:13.310 --> 00:42:16.470
Se las pedí a la dueña, fui a
comer a una casa, y le dije:

00:42:16.470 --> 00:42:17.910
"¿Tienes más servilletas
de esas?"

00:42:17.910 --> 00:42:20.460
Me dijo: "Tengo una caja llena."

00:42:20.460 --> 00:42:22.690
"Si me las da, me las llevo".

00:42:22.690 --> 00:42:23.990
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, all paper
is beautiful for him to use

00:42:23.990 --> 00:42:26.480
in his books and this particular
one, this paper that he loves

00:42:26.480 --> 00:42:28.650
so much, he ate at
somebody's house and she,

00:42:28.650 --> 00:42:30.750
this woman had these
beautiful napkins.

00:42:30.750 --> 00:42:32.050
He said, "Do you have any more?"

00:42:32.050 --> 00:42:34.250
And she said, "Yes,
I have a whole box."

00:42:34.250 --> 00:42:36.820
[risa] And they ended
up in this book.

00:42:36.820 --> 00:42:38.120
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:

00:42:38.120 --> 00:42:39.590
Hay un lenguaje del papel
en estos libros, ¿no?

00:42:39.590 --> 00:42:44.160
El papel es el elemento por
antonomasia distintivo de

00:42:44.160 --> 00:42:45.460
un libro.

00:42:45.460 --> 00:42:49.230
Pero hay en estos libros
un elogio del papel,

00:42:49.230 --> 00:42:57.190
una manera de hablar a través
de los papeles distintos,

00:42:57.190 --> 00:43:05.430
de los distintos papeles,
las distintas texturas.

00:43:05.430 --> 00:43:14.940
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, his
books have so much to do

00:43:14.940 --> 00:43:19.650
with the language
of paper, with paper

00:43:19.650 --> 00:43:21.760
and all its different textures

00:43:21.760 --> 00:43:25.630
and in many ways the books are a
kind of praise for paper, right?

00:43:25.630 --> 00:43:29.200
By definition, books
are made of paper.

00:43:29.200 --> 00:43:33.760
Here, there's a kind
of reflection

00:43:33.760 --> 00:43:36.210
and practice of the paper, so --

00:43:36.210 --> 00:43:37.510
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Papeles distintos,

00:43:37.510 --> 00:43:38.810
aquí hay tres papeles distintos.

00:43:38.810 --> 00:43:41.180
Están conversando
entre los tres.

00:43:41.180 --> 00:43:45.850
Un papel albal, un papel
crepé, un papel blanco.

00:43:45.850 --> 00:43:48.470
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Different
papers kind of interacting

00:43:48.470 --> 00:43:50.620
with each other, crepe
paper and other kinds

00:43:50.620 --> 00:43:51.920
of paper coming together.

00:43:51.920 --> 00:43:53.220
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Como siempre,

00:43:53.220 --> 00:43:55.200
los dibujos están muy también
aportando elementos de contenido

00:43:55.200 --> 00:43:56.500
a estos libros.

00:43:56.500 --> 00:43:57.800
Esta espada que tiene
el nombre de Behar.

00:43:57.800 --> 00:43:59.100
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Also, of course,
the images are very important

00:43:59.100 --> 00:44:00.400
in interacting with the text,

00:44:00.400 --> 00:44:01.700
and this is a sword,
it has my name on it.

00:44:01.700 --> 00:44:03.000
He also added my second
last name, which you know

00:44:03.000 --> 00:44:04.300
in Latin America
we use the patronym

00:44:04.300 --> 00:44:05.600
and the matronym so much here.

00:44:05.600 --> 00:44:06.900
So, in Cuba, I acquired
my other last name.

00:44:06.900 --> 00:44:08.200
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:

00:44:08.200 --> 00:44:09.500
[Ininteligible] Este es un
libro bilingüe también,

00:44:09.500 --> 00:44:10.800
están los cinco poemas en su
edición inglesa y en su versión

00:44:10.800 --> 00:44:12.100
en castellano.

00:44:12.100 --> 00:44:13.400
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, the five
poems, in English and Spanish.

00:44:13.400 --> 00:44:14.700
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Índice, machón.

00:44:14.700 --> 00:44:16.770
Y aquí, entonces, el
número del ejemplar,

00:44:16.770 --> 00:44:19.340
algo que es también muy bonito.

00:44:19.340 --> 00:44:22.080
Estos libros no pasan
de los 50 ejemplares.

00:44:22.080 --> 00:44:24.270
Están entre los 35, los 40,

00:44:24.270 --> 00:44:26.560
los 50 ejemplares,
según sea el caso.

00:44:26.560 --> 00:44:27.920
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So,
each book is numbered.

00:44:27.920 --> 00:44:29.650
This happened to be number 12.

00:44:29.650 --> 00:44:31.960
And he makes these
small editions,

00:44:31.960 --> 00:44:34.620
sometimes, 35, 50 at most.

00:44:34.620 --> 00:44:39.290
So, these are small
edition books.

00:44:39.290 --> 00:44:41.600
Eh, ahora este.

00:44:41.600 --> 00:44:42.900
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Ah, los judíos.

00:44:42.900 --> 00:44:45.200
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Los judíos.

00:44:47.310 --> 00:44:48.610
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Ya.

00:44:48.610 --> 00:44:54.750
Esta es una pequeña antología de
poesía judía, eh, que realizó,

00:44:54.750 --> 00:44:57.870
es decir, al trabajo de
antologación lo hizo Ruth Behar.

00:44:57.870 --> 00:45:01.060
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, this
is a collection of poets,

00:45:01.060 --> 00:45:05.190
by Jewish-Cuban poets, something
that had never been done before,

00:45:05.190 --> 00:45:09.350
that I put together and
it's called, in English,

00:45:09.350 --> 00:45:12.060
it's I'm Loving you
from my Roots,

00:45:12.060 --> 00:45:13.500
is the name of the collection.

00:45:13.500 --> 00:45:15.470
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Después de
leerme la antología y un poco a

00:45:15.470 --> 00:45:21.860
partir del conocimiento que
había tenido de la poesía

00:45:21.860 --> 00:45:28.490
escrita por judíos en el mundo,
pues, entonces aquí salió --

00:45:28.490 --> 00:45:30.540
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, after
reading these poems

00:45:30.540 --> 00:45:33.880
and reading other
poems by Jewish poets,

00:45:33.880 --> 00:45:36.200
Estévez himself wrote
a poem called --

00:45:36.200 --> 00:45:39.220
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Un poema
que escribí a los poetas judíos.

00:45:39.220 --> 00:45:41.400
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Sort of his
response to these poems

00:45:41.400 --> 00:45:42.700
that he wrote, called --

00:45:42.700 --> 00:45:45.040
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Estos libros
también me están sirviendo ahora

00:45:45.040 --> 00:45:50.550
en El Fortín para implicarme
más como escritor y como poeta

00:45:50.550 --> 00:45:52.700
dentro de la dinámica
de los libros.

00:45:52.700 --> 00:45:55.320
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, this is
helping him to really be --

00:45:55.320 --> 00:46:00.670
to involve himself in
the dynamic of bookmaking

00:46:00.670 --> 00:46:04.260
and of writing as well.

00:46:04.260 --> 00:46:07.640
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Vamos
a abrir el libro ahora.

00:46:07.640 --> 00:46:08.940
Zafando allí la rafia.

00:46:08.940 --> 00:46:10.480
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, this
has some rafia fiber

00:46:10.480 --> 00:46:11.920
to open and close the book.

00:46:11.920 --> 00:46:13.790
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
El yute, la rafia,

00:46:13.790 --> 00:46:16.610
el papel de corcho, aserrín.

00:46:16.610 --> 00:46:18.150
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Different
kinds of paper,

00:46:18.150 --> 00:46:20.060
cork and other forms of paper.

00:46:20.060 --> 00:46:23.960
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Cualquier
material es bueno para lograr

00:46:23.960 --> 00:46:27.250
una imagen interesante en estos
libros, una textura interesante.

00:46:27.250 --> 00:46:29.640
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, any
kind of papers is good

00:46:29.640 --> 00:46:33.420
to create exciting
texture in these books.

00:46:33.420 --> 00:46:35.370
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Aquí está esta menora.

00:46:35.370 --> 00:46:37.240
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Here there's
an image of the menorah.

00:46:37.240 --> 00:46:38.920
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:

00:46:38.920 --> 00:46:42.640
Con distintos argumentos
conceptuales,

00:46:42.640 --> 00:46:44.700
que tienen que ver
con el mundo judío.

00:46:44.700 --> 00:46:48.970
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: With different
concepts of Jewish thinking.

00:46:50.110 --> 00:46:54.030
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: El tipo de
letra es otra cosa que en estos

00:46:54.030 --> 00:46:56.960
libros también tiene -- yo creo
que cada libro requiere de su

00:46:56.960 --> 00:46:58.710
propia letra, su
propia tipografía.

00:46:58.710 --> 00:47:01.170
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, each book
requires its own unique form

00:47:01.170 --> 00:47:04.230
of lettering, of font,
and so he also works

00:47:04.230 --> 00:47:06.440
on that very carefully.

00:47:06.440 --> 00:47:07.910
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Aquí está el prólogo.

00:47:07.910 --> 00:47:09.210
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: The prologue.

00:47:09.210 --> 00:47:12.470
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Y un
poco pensando en los judíos

00:47:12.470 --> 00:47:17.790
fundamentalistas, se me ocurrió
la idea que el fondo del los

00:47:17.790 --> 00:47:19.400
textos fuera negro.

00:47:19.400 --> 00:47:20.700
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So,
he also decided

00:47:20.700 --> 00:47:27.360
to use a black foundation for
this book, thinking of kind of,

00:47:27.360 --> 00:47:29.570
you know, orthodox people.

00:47:29.570 --> 00:47:32.200
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Ahí
están los cuatro poetas.

00:47:32.200 --> 00:47:33.500
Son cuatro, ¿verdad?

00:47:33.500 --> 00:47:34.800
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Son cuatro.

00:47:34.800 --> 00:47:36.100
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Cuatro poetas.

00:47:36.100 --> 00:47:37.400
Están en español,
están en inglés.

00:47:37.400 --> 00:47:38.800
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So,
four poets in Spanish

00:47:38.800 --> 00:47:41.480
and English are included
in this book.

00:47:41.480 --> 00:47:45.360
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Aquí está
el dibujo que divide la parte

00:47:45.360 --> 00:47:48.960
española de la parte -- la
parte en español de la parte

00:47:48.960 --> 00:47:50.260
en inglés.

00:47:50.260 --> 00:47:51.560
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: That
illustration divides the book

00:47:51.560 --> 00:47:52.860
between English and Spanish.

00:47:52.860 --> 00:47:54.160
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Aquí, el otro.

00:47:54.160 --> 00:47:57.090
Ahí termina, aquí empieza.

00:47:57.090 --> 00:48:02.300
Y al final, bueno, el índice
y todas las informaciones que

00:48:02.300 --> 00:48:03.600
llevan estos libros.

00:48:03.600 --> 00:48:05.030
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: The index and all
the information about the book

00:48:05.030 --> 00:48:07.100
and how is made and
the materials

00:48:07.100 --> 00:48:10.390
that were used to make the book.

00:48:10.390 --> 00:48:11.690
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Después ordenamos.

00:48:11.690 --> 00:48:12.990
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Sí,
sí, sí, sí, sí.

00:48:12.990 --> 00:48:14.290
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Vamos, así.

00:48:14.290 --> 00:48:16.770
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Vamos
a seguir con Frida.

00:48:16.770 --> 00:48:20.070
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Frida.

00:48:20.070 --> 00:48:22.750
Aquí está mi poema
a Frida Kahlo.

00:48:22.750 --> 00:48:24.300
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, this
is a poem that he wrote

00:48:24.300 --> 00:48:26.020
and dedicated to Frida Kahlo.

00:48:26.020 --> 00:48:29.300
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Se llama
"Con duro polvo de óleo".

00:48:29.300 --> 00:48:33.680
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: And it's
called "With Tough Oil Paint"

00:48:33.680 --> 00:48:35.770
or Duro polvo de óleo.

00:48:35.770 --> 00:48:37.070
&gt;&gt; Catalina Gómez: Golden dust?

00:48:37.070 --> 00:48:38.370
No?

00:48:38.370 --> 00:48:39.670
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Is
it golden dust?

00:48:39.670 --> 00:48:40.970
&gt;&gt; Catalina Gómez:
¿Polvo de oro?

00:48:40.970 --> 00:48:42.270
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Polvo de óleo.

00:48:42.270 --> 00:48:43.570
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Óleo, óleo.

00:48:43.570 --> 00:48:44.870
&gt;&gt; Catalina Gómez:
Óleo, sorry.

00:48:44.870 --> 00:48:46.170
That's right.

00:48:46.170 --> 00:48:47.470
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Yeh, yeah.

00:48:47.470 --> 00:48:48.770
&gt;&gt; Catalina Gómez: Oil.

00:48:48.770 --> 00:48:50.070
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Oil.

00:48:50.070 --> 00:48:51.370
So, Tough Oil Paint or
something like that.

00:48:51.370 --> 00:48:52.670
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Sobre el dibujo,

00:48:52.670 --> 00:48:53.970
toda la iluminación de esa
cabeza fue hecha a mano,

00:48:53.970 --> 00:48:55.270
los 50 ejemplares, uno a uno.

00:48:55.270 --> 00:48:56.570
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, with
this book, all 50 copies,

00:48:56.570 --> 00:48:57.870
these were all hand-illustrated.

00:48:57.870 --> 00:48:59.170
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:

00:48:59.170 --> 00:49:00.500
La realización del
arete en forma de luna.

00:49:00.500 --> 00:49:04.880
Un pincel, dos pinceles o tres
pinceles, según sea el caso.

00:49:04.880 --> 00:49:06.180
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: We were
discussing this before

00:49:06.180 --> 00:49:09.540
with cataloging, that at the
book fairy sometimes there's one

00:49:09.540 --> 00:49:12.060
paintbrush, sometimes
two, and sometimes three.

00:49:12.060 --> 00:49:15.600
So they're all a little
different from each other.

00:49:15.600 --> 00:49:16.900
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Título.

00:49:16.900 --> 00:49:18.200
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: The title.

00:49:18.200 --> 00:49:20.500
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Autor.

00:49:27.240 --> 00:49:30.070
El texto.

00:49:30.070 --> 00:49:32.270
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: The text,
which is a beautiful poem

00:49:32.270 --> 00:49:35.870
that he wrote and
dedicated to Frida Kahlo.

00:49:35.870 --> 00:49:38.170
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Está largo.

00:49:39.260 --> 00:49:41.830
Aquí el machón, con su sorpresa.

00:49:41.830 --> 00:49:46.340
Estos libros siempre están
convocándonos a la sorpresa.

00:49:46.340 --> 00:49:48.330
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: And then,
there's a surprise.

00:49:48.330 --> 00:49:51.970
It's like the machon, the
information about the book.

00:49:54.380 --> 00:49:59.390
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Y creo que
es una de las cosas que hace que

00:49:59.390 --> 00:50:03.240
interactuemos con el libro,
es que lo podamos tocar,

00:50:03.240 --> 00:50:06.360
podamos desplegar los
papeles que tiene,

00:50:06.360 --> 00:50:09.720
podamos abrir este tipo
de informaciones también.

00:50:09.720 --> 00:50:11.210
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, one of
the things that allows us

00:50:11.210 --> 00:50:14.530
to interact with the book is the
way they are, these folded parts

00:50:14.530 --> 00:50:17.910
of the book, and we can interact
with it and surprise ourselves

00:50:17.910 --> 00:50:22.000
as we open and look
through the book.

00:50:22.000 --> 00:50:23.300
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Y detrás,

00:50:23.300 --> 00:50:28.020
el símbolo de El Fortín sobre
los ojos de Frida Kahlo.

00:50:28.020 --> 00:50:30.630
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: The symbol
of El Fortín at the back

00:50:30.630 --> 00:50:34.010
over Frida Kahlo's eyes.

00:50:34.010 --> 00:50:35.310
Eh, Edith.

00:50:35.310 --> 00:50:36.610
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Edith.

00:50:36.610 --> 00:50:42.920
Esta es una -- la tercera
edición ya de este poema.

00:50:42.920 --> 00:50:45.830
Es la primera vez que tiene
una edición de un libro

00:50:45.830 --> 00:50:47.650
completamente hecho a mano.

00:50:47.650 --> 00:50:50.360
La figura de Edith Piaf
está aquí, en la foto,

00:50:50.360 --> 00:50:53.670
pegada sobre una concha marina
transparente, muy clarita.

00:50:53.670 --> 00:50:55.750
Es una concha, es bueno tocarla.

00:50:55.750 --> 00:50:58.290
Estos libros, yo sé que
no los dejan tocar mucho,

00:50:58.290 --> 00:51:01.420
pero son muy buenos para tocar,
porque hay distintas texturas,

00:51:01.420 --> 00:51:06.290
y aquí está el yute, aquí, la
concha marina, aquí, el algodón.

00:51:06.290 --> 00:51:08.550
Se me olvida que tú
tienes que traducir.

00:51:08.550 --> 00:51:09.850
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: No, no, sí.

00:51:09.850 --> 00:51:11.320
So, this is a book
dedicated to Edith Piaf.

00:51:11.320 --> 00:51:15.650
Again, it's a poem that Estévez
wrote and it's the third time

00:51:15.650 --> 00:51:20.060
or third edition of this poem,
and it has a seashell there

00:51:20.060 --> 00:51:22.850
on the cover with
her image over it,

00:51:22.850 --> 00:51:24.990
and he says that
it's really nice

00:51:24.990 --> 00:51:27.080
to touch it even though he
knows that we are not encouraged

00:51:27.080 --> 00:51:29.390
to touch the books that much
at the Library of Congress,

00:51:29.390 --> 00:51:32.520
but it feels very nice
to touch this cover.

00:51:32.520 --> 00:51:35.820
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Aquí está.

00:51:38.110 --> 00:51:40.080
Es como una carpeta.

00:51:40.080 --> 00:51:43.100
Solo está agarrado
por este cordel.

00:51:43.100 --> 00:51:46.710
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, this
is kind of like, like a --

00:51:46.710 --> 00:51:49.550
almost like a portfolio
just held together with a -

00:51:49.550 --> 00:51:53.030
with this bit of wool
or string in the center.

00:51:53.030 --> 00:51:55.610
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Este es
un libro español-francés,

00:51:55.610 --> 00:51:56.910
bilingüe.

00:51:56.910 --> 00:51:59.200
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: This one is
Spanish-French bilingual.

00:51:59.200 --> 00:52:00.500
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:

00:52:00.500 --> 00:52:01.940
Para homenajear a Edith
Piaf también con su idioma.

00:52:01.940 --> 00:52:03.460
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: To
honor Edith Piaf --

00:52:03.460 --> 00:52:04.760
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Con su lengua madre.

00:52:04.760 --> 00:52:07.090
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: With
her mother tongue.

00:52:07.090 --> 00:52:12.970
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Y
entonces, aquí, está el poema.

00:52:16.070 --> 00:52:17.490
En español.

00:52:17.490 --> 00:52:19.220
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Here's
the poem in Spanish.

00:52:19.220 --> 00:52:20.520
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Y también en francés.

00:52:20.520 --> 00:52:23.040
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: And in French.

00:52:23.040 --> 00:52:26.220
&gt;&gt; Catalina Gómez: So, wow.

00:52:26.220 --> 00:52:27.520
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Ahora sí,

00:52:27.520 --> 00:52:29.480
tenemos que doblarlo
para poder plegarlo.

00:52:29.480 --> 00:52:32.020
Para poder seguir
hay que doblarlo.

00:52:32.020 --> 00:52:34.130
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: [Risa] This book
has some complicated engineering

00:52:34.130 --> 00:52:37.970
too, as you see, getting
them to fold properly.

00:52:39.040 --> 00:52:43.160
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Yo creo que
es una manera distinta de mirar

00:52:43.160 --> 00:52:45.720
al libro y vengo haciendo
esto hace más de 30 años ya.

00:52:45.720 --> 00:52:47.780
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: It's another way
to look at the book or think

00:52:47.780 --> 00:52:51.290
about books and he's been
doing this for over 30 years.

00:52:51.290 --> 00:52:54.240
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Me da gusto
poder cada vez experimentar con

00:52:54.240 --> 00:52:58.140
algo distinto, darle a
cada libro su carácter,

00:52:58.140 --> 00:53:01.160
darle a cada libro su discurso.

00:53:01.160 --> 00:53:05.130
Eso me da un reto, es un reto
para mí como artista tratar de

00:53:05.130 --> 00:53:08.970
encontrar qué llevará
este libro, qué material,

00:53:08.970 --> 00:53:10.910
qué dibujo, qué letra.

00:53:10.910 --> 00:53:12.770
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, he really
takes joy in being able

00:53:12.770 --> 00:53:16.850
to make these books and it's
a wonderful artistic challenge

00:53:16.850 --> 00:53:19.550
each book, to figure out what
is this book going to need,

00:53:19.550 --> 00:53:22.320
what kind of paper,
design, lettering

00:53:22.320 --> 00:53:26.460
and to reconstruct
new books every time,

00:53:26.460 --> 00:53:28.790
construct new books every time.

00:53:31.170 --> 00:53:32.760
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Entonces, aquí al final,

00:53:32.760 --> 00:53:34.840
donde uno parece que
no va a ver nada más --

00:53:34.840 --> 00:53:36.780
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: And here, when
you think there's nothing more

00:53:36.780 --> 00:53:40.860
to discover, then you
come and now look at this.

00:53:40.860 --> 00:53:43.430
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Aquí están
estos ángeles para Edith Piaf.

00:53:43.430 --> 00:53:45.720
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: These are
angels for Edith Piaf.

00:53:45.720 --> 00:53:47.220
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Delante de la Torre Eiffel.

00:53:47.220 --> 00:53:49.800
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: And in
front of the Eiffel Tower.

00:53:53.330 --> 00:53:55.630
Yeah, ahá.

00:53:58.170 --> 00:53:59.470
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Y al fondo,

00:53:59.470 --> 00:54:02.610
el faro de El Fortín
convertido en la Torre Eiffel,

00:54:02.610 --> 00:54:05.250
la Torre Eiffel convertida
en el faro de El Fortín.

00:54:05.250 --> 00:54:07.320
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: And the
back cover, the lighthouse

00:54:07.320 --> 00:54:10.460
of El Fortín transformed
into the Eiffel Tower.

00:54:10.460 --> 00:54:12.620
Las damas cubanas.

00:54:12.620 --> 00:54:13.920
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Yeah.

00:54:13.920 --> 00:54:15.220
Un momentico.

00:54:15.220 --> 00:54:17.520
Un traguito de agua.

00:54:20.210 --> 00:54:24.610
Las damas cubanas es la primer
aantología que hizo Ediciones

00:54:24.610 --> 00:54:25.930
El Fortín.

00:54:25.930 --> 00:54:29.030
En este caso, hay
33 poetas cubanas.

00:54:29.030 --> 00:54:30.750
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, this
is the first anthology

00:54:30.750 --> 00:54:35.550
that El Fortín produced
of 33 Cuban women poets.

00:54:35.550 --> 00:54:37.650
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Comenzamos
con Gertrudis Gómez de

00:54:37.650 --> 00:54:47.710
Avellaneda y terminamos con una
mujer que ahora tiene 50 años,

00:54:47.710 --> 00:54:50.580
que es Damaris Calderón.

00:54:50.580 --> 00:54:56.750
No quisimos meternos en el mundo
de las nuevas y las novísimas,

00:54:56.750 --> 00:54:58.580
sino llegar a ese
rango nada más.

00:54:58.580 --> 00:55:00.620
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So,
it's a book that begins

00:55:00.620 --> 00:55:04.310
with Gertrudis Gómez
de Avellaneda, a very,

00:55:04.310 --> 00:55:08.660
very important poet of
the colonial period,

00:55:08.660 --> 00:55:16.890
and ends with a poet who's now
50 years old, Damaris Calderón.

00:55:16.890 --> 00:55:19.990
Que ella vive en Chile, ¿no?

00:55:19.990 --> 00:55:23.680
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: En
Chile vive, en Chile.

00:55:23.680 --> 00:55:24.980
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar.

00:55:24.980 --> 00:55:26.280
In Chile, lives in Chile.

00:55:26.280 --> 00:55:28.110
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: El juego
con la máscara es a partir de un

00:55:28.110 --> 00:55:35.330
eslógan que tiene la antología
que dice que la poesía es una

00:55:35.330 --> 00:55:43.620
máscara que el corazón se
pone para convertir el dolor

00:55:43.620 --> 00:55:44.920
en belleza.

00:55:44.920 --> 00:55:46.220
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, the use

00:55:46.220 --> 00:55:50.460
of the mask is a very
important symbol in this book.

00:55:50.460 --> 00:55:53.220
It comes from a line
that he quotes

00:55:53.220 --> 00:55:55.600
at the very, very
end of the book.

00:55:55.600 --> 00:55:59.010
¿Podría ver la frase otra vez?

00:55:59.010 --> 00:56:00.310
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Sí.

00:56:00.310 --> 00:56:01.610
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: The poetry --

00:56:01.610 --> 00:56:02.910
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Está al final.

00:56:02.910 --> 00:56:04.210
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Poetry
is a mask --

00:56:04.210 --> 00:56:05.510
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Espera.

00:56:05.510 --> 00:56:06.810
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Ahí está.

00:56:06.810 --> 00:56:08.110
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Aquí.

00:56:08.110 --> 00:56:09.410
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Ahá.

00:56:09.410 --> 00:56:10.710
The poetry is a mask that
the heart wears in order

00:56:10.710 --> 00:56:12.010
to transform pain into beauty.

00:56:12.010 --> 00:56:13.310
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: ¿Ya?

00:56:13.310 --> 00:56:14.610
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Mm-hm.

00:56:14.610 --> 00:56:15.910
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Entonces,

00:56:15.910 --> 00:56:17.210
están estas mascaras
en cerámica,

00:56:17.210 --> 00:56:18.510
completamente hechas
especialmente para este

00:56:18.510 --> 00:56:19.810
libro también.

00:56:19.810 --> 00:56:21.110
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So,
these ceramic masks

00:56:21.110 --> 00:56:22.410
that were made specifically
for this book.

00:56:22.410 --> 00:56:23.710
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Estos fondos
son retazos de unas sobrecamas

00:56:23.710 --> 00:56:25.010
que me encontré en venta
muy baratas en Matanzas,

00:56:25.010 --> 00:56:26.310
y las compramos y las
recortamos, todas las limpiamos.

00:56:26.310 --> 00:56:27.610
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, the cover was
made from some old bed covers

00:56:27.610 --> 00:56:28.910
that he found in Matanzas
and cut up and transformed

00:56:28.910 --> 00:56:30.210
into this cover, this kind

00:56:30.210 --> 00:56:31.510
of plush-looking
cover for the book.

00:56:31.510 --> 00:56:32.810
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Esta
es la humedad que lo pega,

00:56:32.810 --> 00:56:34.110
la humedad de Cuba.

00:56:34.110 --> 00:56:35.410
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: That's
Cuban humidity [risa].

00:56:35.410 --> 00:56:36.710
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Están
major aquí en las cajas,

00:56:36.710 --> 00:56:38.010
que aquí las inventaron,

00:56:38.010 --> 00:56:39.310
horizontales, aquí
están perfecto.

00:56:39.310 --> 00:56:40.610
Yo, de verdad, realmente respeto
mucho estas colecciones de

00:56:40.610 --> 00:56:41.910
Michigan, de Misuri, de
la Universidad de Miami,

00:56:41.910 --> 00:56:43.210
la de la Biblioteca del
Congreso, que es fabulosa.

00:56:43.210 --> 00:56:49.930
La conocí desde el
evento en Misuri,

00:56:49.930 --> 00:56:57.510
que ella expuso el sistema
que encontraron para almacenar

00:56:57.510 --> 00:56:58.810
estos libros.

00:56:58.810 --> 00:57:02.160
Son libros frágiles, son
libros enemigos de la humedad.

00:57:02.160 --> 00:57:04.560
Disculpa. I'm sorry,

00:57:04.560 --> 00:57:05.860
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So,

00:57:05.860 --> 00:57:11.620
he's discussing how these
books are fragile and enemies

00:57:11.620 --> 00:57:16.380
of humidity, and [fonética]
Gina Truise, at the conference

00:57:16.380 --> 00:57:21.670
that we were at a few years ago,
discussed all the challenges

00:57:21.670 --> 00:57:23.090
of conserving the books.

00:57:23.090 --> 00:57:27.640
And he's so glad that the books
are being conserved in places

00:57:27.640 --> 00:57:31.770
like the Library of Congress
and various universities,

00:57:31.770 --> 00:57:35.690
and that they are, you know,
being maintained so beautifully,

00:57:35.690 --> 00:57:38.040
'cause they are very, very
difficult to maintain.

00:57:38.040 --> 00:57:42.090
They are produced in Cuba, but
difficult to maintain in Cuba

00:57:42.090 --> 00:57:43.420
with all the humidity.

00:57:43.420 --> 00:57:45.650
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
South California,

00:57:45.650 --> 00:57:48.460
South California también
tiene una buena colección,

00:57:48.460 --> 00:57:50.640
[initeligible] una que se
[ininteligible] en Miami,

00:57:50.640 --> 00:57:54.660
pero ella dio una lección en
Misuri sobre cómo se almacenan

00:57:54.660 --> 00:57:55.960
estos libros, que me
parece aquí perfecto.

00:57:55.960 --> 00:57:57.460
Y uno siente una seguridad
muy grande de saber que hay

00:57:57.460 --> 00:57:58.900
instituciones que los
tienen, porque son frágiles,

00:57:58.900 --> 00:58:00.370
son delicados, tan hechos
con materiales reciclados.

00:58:00.370 --> 00:58:01.670
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, he is so glad

00:58:01.670 --> 00:58:02.970
that books are conserved
so wonderfully here.

00:58:02.970 --> 00:58:04.270
He knows these are very
fragile books, they are made --

00:58:04.270 --> 00:58:05.570
they are delicate books,
they are made with a lot

00:58:05.570 --> 00:58:06.870
of recycled materials.

00:58:06.870 --> 00:58:08.170
They are very, very
hard to conserve.

00:58:08.170 --> 00:58:09.470
And so, he's so grateful
and so glad she did --

00:58:09.470 --> 00:58:10.770
that you shared that
information,

00:58:10.770 --> 00:58:12.070
and hopefully we'll
have time afterwards

00:58:12.070 --> 00:58:13.370
to say a little bit
more about that too.

00:58:13.370 --> 00:58:14.670
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Aquí
ya empieza la Avellaneda.

00:58:14.670 --> 00:58:15.970
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So,
that's the first poem.

