and did a lot of
research into the history

00:58:55.610 --> 00:58:57.970
of women's poetic
writing in Cuba.

00:59:01.040 --> 00:59:03.130
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Y el final del libro.

00:59:03.130 --> 00:59:04.530
¿Ya no nos quedan?

00:59:04.530 --> 00:59:05.830
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Ya.

00:59:05.830 --> 00:59:07.130
Ya estamos.

00:59:07.130 --> 00:59:08.430
Ya.

00:59:08.430 --> 00:59:09.730
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Estamos para los únicos.

00:59:09.730 --> 00:59:11.030
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Estamos
para los únicos.

00:59:11.030 --> 00:59:12.330
Sí.

00:59:12.330 --> 00:59:13.630
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
¿Cuál empezamos?

00:59:13.630 --> 00:59:14.930
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Eh.

00:59:14.930 --> 00:59:16.230
Aquí vamos.

00:59:16.230 --> 00:59:18.260
Ponemos a Canción difícil
y ya los dos únicos.

00:59:18.260 --> 00:59:20.170
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Ah,
falta Canción difícil.

00:59:20.170 --> 00:59:21.470
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Sí.

00:59:21.470 --> 00:59:22.770
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
¿Dónde está?

00:59:22.770 --> 00:59:24.070
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Aquí.

00:59:24.070 --> 00:59:25.370
[risa]

00:59:25.370 --> 00:59:26.670
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Este es un
libro de una gran compositora

00:59:26.670 --> 00:59:29.790
cubana, Marta Valdés,
una mujer del feelin.

00:59:29.790 --> 00:59:33.060
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, this is a
very important book of the work

00:59:33.060 --> 00:59:37.840
of Marta Valdés, whose is
an amazing singer, composer,

00:59:37.840 --> 00:59:40.290
a very important person
in what was called

00:59:40.290 --> 00:59:41.620
"the feelin" movement.

00:59:41.620 --> 00:59:45.100
"Feelin", without
the "g" in Spanish.

00:59:45.100 --> 00:59:47.240
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Es una mujer
muy afiliada a la ciudad de

00:59:47.240 --> 00:59:49.490
Matanzas, aunque nació
y vive en la Habana.

00:59:49.490 --> 00:59:52.960
Es muy afiliada a la ciudad de
Matanzas, le ha cantado mucho.

00:59:52.960 --> 00:59:54.430
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, she's
a woman from Habana,

00:59:54.430 --> 00:59:56.860
but she has spent a
lot of time in Matanzas

00:59:56.860 --> 00:59:59.340
and has performed
frequently in Matanzas,

00:59:59.340 --> 01:00:01.120
so she's very close to the city.

01:00:01.120 --> 01:00:02.420
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Por eso,

01:00:02.420 --> 01:00:04.960
esta bolsita tiene un poco
de arena del río San Juan.

01:00:04.960 --> 01:00:07.440
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: This little
bag has a little bit of sand

01:00:07.440 --> 01:00:10.690
from the San Juan river,
which runs through Matanzas.

01:00:10.690 --> 01:00:12.440
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Y estas
cosas se convierten como en

01:00:12.440 --> 01:00:14.690
resguardos para el
propio libro, ¿no?

01:00:14.690 --> 01:00:16.070
De alguna manera, es eso.

01:00:16.070 --> 01:00:17.370
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: These things kind

01:00:17.370 --> 01:00:18.790
of become talismans
for the book.

01:00:18.790 --> 01:00:20.510
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Exacto, talismán, talismán.

01:00:20.510 --> 01:00:22.810
Eso es.

01:00:25.140 --> 01:00:28.350
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Hay una
coincidencia en la fecha.

01:00:28.350 --> 01:00:32.800
Marta Valdés nació el mismo día
que Frida Kahlo, el 6 de julio.

01:00:32.800 --> 01:00:34.100
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So,
it's interesting.

01:00:34.100 --> 01:00:36.140
Marta Valdés was
born on the same day

01:00:36.140 --> 01:00:37.510
as Frida Kahlo, July, 6th.

01:00:37.510 --> 01:00:39.560
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Pero también
la poeta cubana Carilda Oliver y

01:00:39.560 --> 01:00:44.050
Marta Valdés también nacieron
el mismo día, el 6 de julio.

01:00:44.050 --> 01:00:47.900
Aquí está con Carilda,
y aquí está con Frida.

01:00:47.900 --> 01:00:49.270
Nuestra Marta Valdés.

01:00:49.270 --> 01:00:51.750
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Also, the poet
Carilda Oliver Labra was born

01:00:51.750 --> 01:00:53.350
on July, 6th.

01:00:53.350 --> 01:00:56.040
Same day, so she's there
with each of the two poets.

01:00:56.040 --> 01:00:57.600
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Me
gusta indagar también,

01:00:57.600 --> 01:00:59.460
me gusta indagar en el autor.

01:00:59.460 --> 01:01:01.460
No solamente en su
obra, sino en su vida.

01:01:01.460 --> 01:01:03.870
Por eso es que llevo
estos detalles,

01:01:03.870 --> 01:01:07.850
porque me gusta indagar
en la vida del autor.

01:01:07.850 --> 01:01:11.490
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: He likes to
explore the life of the author,

01:01:11.490 --> 01:01:13.100
not just the work of the author.

01:01:13.100 --> 01:01:15.960
So he tries to bring
those things together.

01:01:18.110 --> 01:01:23.050
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Todas
las informaciones de portada,

01:01:23.050 --> 01:01:24.350
portadilla.

01:01:24.350 --> 01:01:28.380
Una nota que le escribe
a las canciones de Marta.

01:01:28.380 --> 01:01:32.260
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: A note that he
wrote to Marta about her songs.

01:01:32.260 --> 01:01:33.560
They are so beautiful.

01:01:33.560 --> 01:01:37.150
If you haven't heard her, look
up the songs of Marta Valdés.

01:01:37.150 --> 01:01:38.690
They are really just
-- very beautiful.

01:01:38.690 --> 01:01:40.310
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Este
es un libro trilingüe,

01:01:40.310 --> 01:01:41.800
español-francés-inglés.

01:01:41.800 --> 01:01:45.410
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: It's trilingual,
Spanish, French and English.

01:01:45.410 --> 01:01:47.150
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Primero
están las cinco canciones

01:01:47.150 --> 01:01:48.450
en español.

01:01:48.450 --> 01:01:50.160
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: There's
five songs in the book.

01:01:50.160 --> 01:01:54.900
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Después vienen en inglés.

01:01:54.900 --> 01:02:00.250
Tiene -- cada sección tiene
este separador amarillo.

01:02:00.250 --> 01:02:04.200
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, each section
has this image painted yellow.

01:02:04.200 --> 01:02:06.720
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Y, al final, entonces,

01:02:06.720 --> 01:02:10.380
las canciones en francés, las
mismas canciones en francés.

01:02:10.380 --> 01:02:12.960
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: At the
end, the songs in French.

01:02:15.050 --> 01:02:16.350
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Un dibujo largo.

01:02:16.350 --> 01:02:20.950
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: And now a
beautiful illustration.

01:02:28.040 --> 01:02:29.340
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Y
llegamos aquí al final.

01:02:29.340 --> 01:02:32.250
Otra vez, manchón,
guardas y todo lo demás.

01:02:32.250 --> 01:02:33.550
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Bello.

01:02:33.550 --> 01:02:34.850
Entonces ya [ininteligible]

01:02:34.850 --> 01:02:41.670
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Paralelo
a este trabajo de los libros

01:02:41.670 --> 01:02:47.000
seriados, es decir, a estos
libros que son originales

01:02:47.000 --> 01:02:49.750
multiples, paralelo
a este trabajo.

01:02:49.750 --> 01:02:51.690
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, parallel
to this work that he does,

01:02:51.690 --> 01:02:56.460
which he considers to
be multiple originals,

01:02:56.460 --> 01:02:59.160
so that's what we've been
looking at now, now he's going

01:02:59.160 --> 01:03:02.240
to share these one-of-a-kind
books,

01:03:02.240 --> 01:03:04.020
these unique artist's books.

01:03:04.020 --> 01:03:05.730
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: También
desde la década de los '80,

01:03:05.730 --> 01:03:10.910
desde finales de los '80, vengo
realizando ejemplares únicos.

01:03:10.910 --> 01:03:12.670
Un libro completamente
artístico,

01:03:12.670 --> 01:03:15.920
con una sola copia, sin más.

01:03:15.920 --> 01:03:17.560
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So,
since the 80s,

01:03:17.560 --> 01:03:21.020
he started producing these
again one-of-a-kind books

01:03:21.020 --> 01:03:23.550
that have no further copies.

01:03:23.550 --> 01:03:24.850
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:

01:03:24.850 --> 01:03:27.760
Venía preparado para
mostrarles tres voluminosos,

01:03:27.760 --> 01:03:34.040
grandes libros únicos, pero nos
jugó una mala pasada la aduana

01:03:34.040 --> 01:03:36.370
en Cuba y van a llegar
esta noche.

01:03:36.370 --> 01:03:38.900
Así que van a llegar
después de la presentación.

01:03:38.900 --> 01:03:40.200
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So,
he shipped along

01:03:40.200 --> 01:03:42.750
with his bags three big boxes
with spectacular new books

01:03:42.750 --> 01:03:45.090
that he produced
specifically for this event,

01:03:45.090 --> 01:03:49.130
but unfortunately, they were
held back at customs in Habana

01:03:49.130 --> 01:03:50.480
and didn't make it
on his flight,

01:03:50.480 --> 01:03:51.780
but they are arriving tonight,

01:03:51.780 --> 01:03:54.790
and we hope to show
them on Saturday.

01:03:54.790 --> 01:03:58.130
Very beautiful, ambitious,
gorgeous books.

01:03:58.130 --> 01:04:01.660
So, we only have two of
these one-of-a-kind books

01:04:01.660 --> 01:04:02.960
to show you today.

01:04:02.960 --> 01:04:05.610
But these are quite spectacular
as well, and if you can come

01:04:05.610 --> 01:04:08.120
on Saturday, you'll
see the brand-new ones

01:04:08.120 --> 01:04:11.230
that he has just made, that
are really, really fantastic.

01:04:11.230 --> 01:04:13.340
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Sobre
una caja de pinturas, ¿no?

01:04:13.340 --> 01:04:16.790
Una caja de materiales
de trabajo.

01:04:16.790 --> 01:04:20.170
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, this book
is made from a paint box.

01:04:20.170 --> 01:04:25.380
¿Le cuento que yo
te la había regalado?

01:04:25.380 --> 01:04:26.680
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Sí, sí, claro.

01:04:26.680 --> 01:04:27.980
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So,
the story, briefly.

01:04:27.980 --> 01:04:32.620
So, many, many years ago,
I gave him this wooden box

01:04:32.620 --> 01:04:36.330
that was filled with paints and
brushes as a gift, and then,

01:04:36.330 --> 01:04:39.410
years later, he gave it back
to me as this work of art.

01:04:39.410 --> 01:04:41.670
[risa] And that's --
and it's called --

01:04:41.670 --> 01:04:43.300
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
He devuelto el regalo.

01:04:43.300 --> 01:04:44.600
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: He
returned it to me.

01:04:44.600 --> 01:04:46.550
Pensando en mi amiga Ruth Behar.

01:04:46.550 --> 01:04:50.060
Thinking about my
friend, Ruth Behar.

01:04:50.060 --> 01:04:54.580
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Es un
poema del libro "La vena rota".

01:04:54.580 --> 01:05:02.150
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, it's a poem
from a book, a beautiful book

01:05:02.150 --> 01:05:04.750
that he wrote, called
"La vena rota."

01:05:04.750 --> 01:05:06.050
"The Broken Vein".

01:05:06.050 --> 01:05:07.710
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Entonces,
todos estos materiales,

01:05:07.710 --> 01:05:13.880
que están ilustrando un
poco el poema que, a su vez,

01:05:13.880 --> 01:05:18.000
se basa en un poema de Dulce
María que habla de cuando el

01:05:18.000 --> 01:05:22.520
hombre se levanta el
abrigo, en el muelle frío.

01:05:22.520 --> 01:05:23.820
Te acuerdas, ¿verdad?

01:05:23.820 --> 01:05:25.120
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Sí, me encanta.

01:05:25.120 --> 01:05:26.520
So, this is a poem that
Estévez wrote for me,

01:05:26.520 --> 01:05:29.670
but it references a poem
by Dulce María Loynaz

01:05:29.670 --> 01:05:33.140
about the traveler, who's
lifting up his collar, you know,

01:05:33.140 --> 01:05:34.440
to be met by somebody
at the port.

01:05:34.440 --> 01:05:35.740
So, it references that --
the lines from that poem.

01:05:35.740 --> 01:05:37.040
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: A
veces, uno se pregunta,

01:05:37.040 --> 01:05:38.340
¿dónde está el texto?

01:05:38.340 --> 01:05:39.640
Porque si es un libro,
tiene que tener un texto.

01:05:39.640 --> 01:05:40.940
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Sometimes,

01:05:40.940 --> 01:05:42.240
you ask yourself,
"Where's the text?"

01:05:42.240 --> 01:05:43.540
If this is a book, it's got
to have the text somewhere.

01:05:43.540 --> 01:05:44.840
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Aquí, en esta cajita.

01:05:44.840 --> 01:05:47.140
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So,
in this little box.

01:05:51.040 --> 01:05:52.340
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez:
Esta [initeligible]

01:05:52.340 --> 01:05:53.640
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Ups.

01:05:53.640 --> 01:05:54.940
[risa]

01:05:54.940 --> 01:05:56.240
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: De acordeón.

01:05:56.240 --> 01:05:59.360
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: This
is like an accordion.

01:05:59.360 --> 01:06:00.660
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: El texto.

01:06:00.660 --> 01:06:01.960
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: There's the text.

01:06:01.960 --> 01:06:05.800
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Y creo que
hay algo más, pero en el fondo.

01:06:05.800 --> 01:06:08.580
Si mal no recuerdo, ¿o no?

01:06:08.580 --> 01:06:09.880
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Sí, sí, sí.

01:06:09.880 --> 01:06:14.210
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Aquí hay
una foto de Dulce María Loynaz

01:06:14.210 --> 01:06:18.710
porque, de alguna manera, es
la que nos unió en este poema,

01:06:18.710 --> 01:06:22.720
donde estamos ella y estoy yo,

01:06:22.720 --> 01:06:26.670
pero un poco a través de la
obra de Dulce María también.

01:06:26.670 --> 01:06:30.110
Y por detrás, entonces,
dice -- habla de esta --

01:06:30.110 --> 01:06:34.850
es una foto original que hizo
un fotógrafo de Matanzas a Dulce

01:06:34.850 --> 01:06:38.890
María, y me la regaló, y
yo la añadí a este libro.

01:06:38.890 --> 01:06:41.030
La quiero tanto que me
desprendí de la foto y se la di.

01:06:41.030 --> 01:06:43.040
[ Risas ]

01:06:43.040 --> 01:06:44.970
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, this
is an original photo

01:06:44.970 --> 01:06:47.840
of Dulce María Loynaz,
de great Cuban poet

01:06:47.840 --> 01:06:51.990
who won the Cervantes prize,
and it was a real photo

01:06:51.990 --> 01:06:54.670
that he had gotten or that
a Matanzas' photographer has

01:06:54.670 --> 01:06:56.480
taken, and he likes me so much

01:06:56.480 --> 01:06:59.370
that he gave me this
photo that he had.

01:06:59.370 --> 01:07:00.670
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Ya
no me acordaba de eso.

01:07:00.670 --> 01:07:01.970
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: No.

01:07:01.970 --> 01:07:04.310
He had forgotten about this.

01:07:04.310 --> 01:07:06.400
And in a way, Dulce
María Loynaz,

01:07:06.400 --> 01:07:08.430
like I said in my
introductory remark was kind

01:07:08.430 --> 01:07:11.680
of like the bridge between
us, she was the first poet

01:07:11.680 --> 01:07:14.690
that I learned about, Cuban poet
that I learned about from him,

01:07:14.690 --> 01:07:18.450
and she really -- was
really important to me

01:07:18.450 --> 01:07:23.040
and very important to Estévez,
and became kind of the bridge,

01:07:23.040 --> 01:07:25.940
one of the bridges between us.

01:07:25.940 --> 01:07:27.950
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Bueno,
entonces, para terminar,

01:07:27.950 --> 01:07:29.250
vamos a hablar un poquito.

01:07:29.250 --> 01:07:32.410
Con este iba a empezar yo la
presentación que iba a hacer,

01:07:32.410 --> 01:07:34.120
pero la vida le hace
esas cosas a uno,

01:07:34.120 --> 01:07:37.470
y es con el que voy a cerrar.

01:07:37.470 --> 01:07:38.770
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, déjame decir.

01:07:38.770 --> 01:07:41.770
So, he was going to begin, if
the other books had arrived

01:07:41.770 --> 01:07:44.570
with his bags, he was going
to begin with this book,

01:07:44.570 --> 01:07:45.950
and then end with the others,

01:07:45.950 --> 01:07:49.020
but instead we're going
to end with this one.

01:07:49.020 --> 01:07:50.320
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Bueno,

01:07:50.320 --> 01:07:55.300
he hecho una larga colección de
ejemplares únicos de libros-arte

01:07:55.300 --> 01:08:00.210
basados en los Versos
sencillos de José Martí,

01:08:00.210 --> 01:08:02.150
que es un libro espléndido.

01:08:02.150 --> 01:08:04.280
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, he's made
many unique one-of-a-kind

01:08:04.280 --> 01:08:08.200
artist's books based on the work
of José Martí, particularly,

01:08:08.200 --> 01:08:11.940
the "Simple Verses",
the "Versos sencillos".

01:08:14.570 --> 01:08:16.710
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Y está
por todas partes Ediciones

01:08:16.710 --> 01:08:18.310
El Fortín.

01:08:18.310 --> 01:08:21.660
Bellamar es Matanzas, para
mí, Bellamar es Matanzas.

01:08:21.660 --> 01:08:24.930
Yo le he cambiado el nombre
a esa ciudad porque tiene un

01:08:24.930 --> 01:08:26.850
nombre horrendo y sanguinario.

01:08:26.850 --> 01:08:30.170
Entonces, he empezado una
campana que a lo mejor florece

01:08:30.170 --> 01:08:31.500
alguna vez.

01:08:31.500 --> 01:08:34.040
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, he has
begun a campaign in the city

01:08:34.040 --> 01:08:37.020
of Matanzas, because he doesn't
like the name of his city.

01:08:37.020 --> 01:08:40.840
"Matanzas" literally means
"slaughter" or "killings",

01:08:40.840 --> 01:08:42.410
so it's a very bloody name.

01:08:42.410 --> 01:08:44.260
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Di lo
que quiere decir en inglés

01:08:44.260 --> 01:08:45.560
"matanzas".

01:08:45.560 --> 01:08:46.870
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: Sí,
sí, ya lo dije.

01:08:46.870 --> 01:08:49.230
So, it's a name that he doesn't
like, a very violent name,

01:08:49.230 --> 01:08:53.070
and so he's actually begun this
campaign to change the name

01:08:53.070 --> 01:08:56.600
of the city to Bellamar,
which means "beautiful ocean."

01:08:56.600 --> 01:09:02.060
So, he writes, as you
saw, he writes Bellamar,

01:09:02.060 --> 01:09:06.430
that the books are made in
Bellamar rather than Matanzas.

01:09:06.430 --> 01:09:08.690
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Es
un nombre más suave.

01:09:08.690 --> 01:09:10.570
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: It's
a nicer, softer name.

01:09:10.570 --> 01:09:11.870
&gt;&gt; Rolando Estévez: Ya.

01:09:11.870 --> 01:09:16.970
Entonces, aquí adentro
está esta caja de yute.

01:09:21.040 --> 01:09:25.590
Forrada de girasoles, que
son los girasoles de Ochun.

01:09:25.590 --> 01:09:28.650
&gt;&gt; Ruth Behar: So, here's this
beautiful line with burlap,

01:09:28.650 --> 01:09:31.400
and then at the top,
