because we're just huge fans

01:14:06.550 --> 01:14:10.920
of the Vigía, Ediciones
Vigía, and actually came

01:14:10.920 --> 01:14:15.030
to know the collection
through Gina Truise who --

01:14:15.030 --> 01:14:17.490
she works in preservation, and
they already mentioned her.

01:14:17.490 --> 01:14:21.590
She has been involved with this
collection, did several trips

01:14:21.590 --> 01:14:24.920
to Cuba before having her
job here at the library

01:14:24.920 --> 01:14:30.340
and was extremely involved
with bringing, you know,

01:14:30.340 --> 01:14:35.580
books to United States and also,
I think, she spent time there

01:14:35.580 --> 01:14:37.870
and even worked with them.

01:14:37.870 --> 01:14:40.970
But she did a great
presentation of the books,

01:14:40.970 --> 01:14:47.040
and I remember how I was just
like, you know, in cloud nine.

01:14:47.040 --> 01:14:51.720
It was just like a such
an amazing discovery,

01:14:51.720 --> 01:14:55.150
and they just [ininteligible]
to everyone who's sees them,

01:14:55.150 --> 01:14:57.250
because there's nothing
like them.

01:14:57.250 --> 01:15:00.660
But they're just exquisite.

01:15:00.660 --> 01:15:03.490
All I want to say is that
what also was beautiful

01:15:03.490 --> 01:15:09.200
about these collections is just
to see sort of what can happen

01:15:09.200 --> 01:15:12.190
in the library to make
these collections available

01:15:12.190 --> 01:15:16.320
to the public, and again I am
here as a messanger because most

01:15:16.320 --> 01:15:19.210
of this work was done by
other people in the library,

01:15:19.210 --> 01:15:23.840
like Gina in preservation
building this amazinga boxes to,

01:15:23.840 --> 01:15:29.820
you know, to try to preserve
this as long as we can.

01:15:29.820 --> 01:15:35.550
They are made with all these
kinds of materials like,

01:15:35.550 --> 01:15:40.470
you know, fluid materials,
tree bark and things

01:15:40.470 --> 01:15:44.930
that [ininteigible] are
not the best for, you know,

01:15:44.930 --> 01:15:46.870
posterity, I would say.

01:15:46.870 --> 01:15:49.620
So, it's just amazing the
work that preservation does.

01:15:49.620 --> 01:15:52.210
And in the display I think
you saw some of the boxes

01:15:52.210 --> 01:15:56.430
that are made for --
to sort the Vigía books

01:15:56.430 --> 01:16:01.120
and it's really amazing because
the actually build the boxes

01:16:01.120 --> 01:16:05.140
depending on the shape of
the book, and it's amazing,

01:16:05.140 --> 01:16:10.090
because they -- just, there's
so much time and love punt

01:16:10.090 --> 01:16:15.100
into protecting them, and it's
just been wonderful to see that,

01:16:15.100 --> 01:16:17.160
and -- So they are
acid-free boxes

01:16:17.160 --> 01:16:22.580
that actually Gina would explain
to me that they actually buffer

01:16:22.580 --> 01:16:25.340
and they actually
absorb all the acid

01:16:25.340 --> 01:16:28.680
from the materials
so it lasts longer.

01:16:28.680 --> 01:16:33.840
So that's -- it's
really neat to --

01:16:33.840 --> 01:16:38.320
this is like a big operation
here at the Library of Congress,

01:16:38.320 --> 01:16:41.590
and then Barbara Dash who is a
cataloger of this collection,

01:16:41.590 --> 01:16:43.860
which has also been fascinating

01:16:43.860 --> 01:16:48.820
to learn how someone spends
all this time describing

01:16:48.820 --> 01:16:50.800
the material.

01:16:50.800 --> 01:16:54.610
When people search for
these items in our catalog,

01:16:54.610 --> 01:16:56.850
each book has a catalog worker,

01:16:56.850 --> 01:16:59.150
and each book has a
